                    ],
                    "body": "One of the best sessions for neuromuscular training, this drill asks you to progressively build from a cadence of 90 RPM to your MAX over 30 seconds, recover, and repeat several times. Cadence builds improve how you recruit your leg, gluteal, and core muscles throughout your pedal stroke by progressing to your maximal cadence. By reaching your highest cadence possible, you are training the 'on/off' switch in each muscle group to not only work faster but to have less overlap with your other muscle groups. This session trains your hamstring muscles to 'turn off' when your quads 'turn on' and vice-versa, resulting in a more efficient pedal stroke at both high and low cadences.  \n",

            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.amazonaws.com/content/b6529e0b-eab8-46d3-9144-36b9118881a9-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "While the single tempo effort you complete in this session is steady in terms of power, it's the specific cadence targets that set this session apart from other tempo workouts.\n\n\u200b\n\nEven though an effort at 80% of FTP might seem \"easy\", the truth is your body is working at processing oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate as when you are right at FTP. The difference is that the overall stress on your system when riding tempo is considerably less than while riding at FTP. That means you can either have harder days before or after a tempo session (compared to a threshold session) or you can increase the duration of those tempo efforts to make the overall training stimulus equal (or greater) than completing several repeats right at your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis tempo effort is divided into 3 segments of equal duration. While the power is the same across all segments, your target cadence starts and low and increases with each new segment. Starting with a long block of low cadence should fatigue your muscles from the start of your effort. As the effort builds and you create more fatigue, the increased cadence targets will place a greater demand on your cardiovascular system. That will feel like a nice break given the load you have been putting on your muscular system. The cadence targets in the final segment will force your fatigued muscles to maintain good coordination as the faster cadence requires your muscles to switch \"on\" and \"off\" at a faster rate. Between the low-RPM sections and the high-RPM work under fatigue, this tempo session not only helps train your FTP, but also benefits your neuromuscular system.\n\n\u200b\n\nYou can expect your heart rate to remain low for the power targets during the low cadence segment at the start. As the effort progresses and you reach the final 10 minutes of the high rpm segment, your heart rate might go over Z3, which is not something to worry about. While this session appears \"easy\" at first glance, don't be surprised if your legs are feeling it the next day.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: NA\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\nBuild 1: 20 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nBuild 2: 20 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nBuild 3: 20 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n1 hour 15 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "You have the leader's jersey, but then disaster strikes: A crash, an injury, and you're forced to defend your position until the end of the race. Can you hang on under a barrage of attacks? Based on four, ten-minute efforts around threshold, _Defender_ is designed to give you the most bang for your aerobic buck, or in this case, the most Watts at FTP for your Suffering.\n\n\u200b\n\nThere are both psychological as well as physiological benefits to this tremendous workout. Mentally, _Defender_ will improve your sense of pacing for longer efforts near FTP. That's because each effort starts above FTP, and since you're fresh, you'll feel as though you can hold that pace all day. Every two minutes, the pace gradually declines, so you are finishing just below FTP. As the time ticks away, the power targets will drop little by little, but your discomfort will remain about the same. By the fourth effort, you'll find the same efforts far more difficult than in the first. By staying tuned in to what your body is telling you, you'll learn more about managing your efforts around threshold and why it's so important to manage your efforts well at this intensity.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe physiological benefits follow the same lines as those found in The Sufferfest workouts _Who Dares_ or _Fight Club_. Overloading your legs and lungs with efforts above FTP before settling into efforts right at or below FTP forces your body to clear out as many metabolites as possible and process as much oxygen as it can.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhat sets _Defender_ apart is how that overload is delivered. While _Who Dares_ achieves this with short sprints, _Defender_ forces you to spend minutes above FTP before simmering back down. This allows your heart rate and breathing rate to get much closer to what they are during a long, steady-state threshold effort. This ensures that \u201coverload\u201d comes in as a steady drip, rather than the sudden burst like that in _Who Dares_. The lower intensity of this overload also changes the types of metabolites produced and the ratios in which they occur. Not only does this keep the enzymes in your body focused on aerobic metabolism, but your body will also respond with fewer stress hormones. This means you're training your aerobic system by overloading it but doing so in a way that leaves you more ready to hit tomorrow's training just as hard.\n",

            "__typename": "Content",
            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Sustained Efforts",
            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/735d4f76-4498-4692-8761-5cc95033b62c-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. The ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT will be added in a future release.",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "This is one of the most classic interval sessions out there. Whether you're a triathlete, a roadie, a mountain biker, or have simply flipped through cycling magazines looking at whatever workouts they might suggest in their \"5-workouts to make you faster\" articles, you've probably heard of the venerable 2 x 20.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe reason it's so popular is that it's easy to follow, helps teach good pacing, and gives you a great threshold training stimulus.\n\n\u200b\n\nSo what exactly is 2 x 20? Well, it's two 20-minute blocks at an effort just below your FTP.\nMany refer to this intensity as \"sweet spot\", but we prefer \"sub-threshold\", as the real key is to never let your power creep above your FTP. This ensures your effort remains at an intensity you know your body can cope with but that is pretty close to an effort you wouldn't be able to handle for 20 minutes.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe only way you are going to make it through two of these 20-minute efforts is if you pace yourself properly. Everyone feels just fine for the first 5-minutes of the first effort, and most people are tempted to go harder. Do NOT be that person. 99 times out a 100, that person blows up spectacularly in the second interval, and never even makes to the last 10 minutes. Or they have to ride that second interval at lower power, turning it into a Tempo session, which is not the goal.\n\nGetting a sense of how these efforts \"bite\" towards the end is vital to learning how to pace yourself over longer steady state efforts. Whether that is a Time Trial, local Climb, breakaway, Triathlon, or even a good old Power Test. In each of those cases, the pacing is key, seeing how your perception of how hard the effort is can steadily climb even though your power remains the same.\n\n\u200b\n\nSo how do you know if you are doing this one right?\nAs we said, the first 5 minutes should feel relatively easy. Around that 5-minute mark, your heart rate should stop climbing, and settle into 2-5% below your LTHR. If your heart rate is climbing for the entire effort and goes above your LTHR, then you are going too hard.\n\n\u200b\n\nIf you hit the 10-minute mark, your legs feel fine, and your heart rate is still in Zone 3, then you aren't going hard enough.\nIf you have never done a session like this before, you can consider only doing the first 20-minute effort, or even sticking to just the first 15 of each effort. There is no shame in building up to this full session, so don't be afraid to pause and fast forward as needed.\n\n\u200b\n\nNailing this session is really about getting in tune with your body, and understanding what that edge feels like, between a sustainable and an unsustainable effort. That means failing this workout is fairly common, and not at all something to get down about. As long as you learn from the experience\u2014for example, what \"too hard\" feels like 10-minutes in\u2014then you've become a better athlete, even if you didn't make it through the entire workout.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 2\n\nRest between sets: 12 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

This continuous tempo effort will have you alternate between 75 & 85% of FTP every minute. Not only does this help pass the time rather quickly, it will help improve your aerobic fitness. Time spent in this intensity range will help increase your stroke volume (amount of blood your heart can pump every minute), your lactate threshold, and the mitochondrial density of your muscles (mitochondria are the \"power houses\" of the cells that create energy). All of these things are very important parts of aerobic metabolism and performing your best- especially if you like group rides. This is the typical intensity range that most group rides fall into- not a leisurely pace, but not so fast that people are falling off the back within minutes. So if you find that you commonly struggle with group rides, gradually spending more time on workouts at this intensity will have you holding on longer and taking your pulls without missing a beat!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 10\n\nRest between sets: NA\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\nWork: 1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\nSteady: 1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "Smooth like butter. Grace under pressure. It's what we're focusing on in this session as you accumulate plenty of time at a high aerobic workload. A good warm-up leads you into two sets of five 90-second intervals with 3-minutes of \u201crecovery\u201d between each. Instead of full gas intervals followed by super low-intensity recovery, these efforts are hard. Still, the real sting (and training benefit) comes from the incomplete recovery you face between intervals. These \u201crecovery\u201d efforts are at the upper end of Z2, meaning you still need quite a bit of oxygen to keep that power churning.\n\n\u200b\n\nBy keeping the intervals themselves under your Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP) AND not allowing complete recovery, your body will burn through your Anaerobic Capacity (AC) before the end of each set, forcing your body to produce that power aerobically. For those of you who have tackled the Full Frontal fitness test, your body goes through that same transition near the 3-minute mark of the 5-minute test. With this session, not only is it less painful, but you also end up with more total time in that aerobically-dependent state. Endurance sports are all about churning through as much oxygen as possible, and few other workouts see you churning this hard and for this long.\n",

The only problem is that you're stuck with a first-time Directeur Sportif. Can you pull off the win?\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session is all about Max Aerobic Power (MAP), also known as VO2 max training. MAP refers to the maximum rate of oxygen delivery and uptake by your body and is an important metric in the world of endurance sports. During this 30-minute session, you\u2019ll be doing five MAP targeted intervals. The first is 3 minutes long, and each successive interval gets 30 seconds shorter until you end with a final effort of \u201cjust\u201d 60 seconds. The structure of each interval varies to keep you on your toes, some with increases in power, some with decreases.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe cadence targets for this session are generally going to be a little higher than \u201ccomfortable\u201d for most people \u2013 and for a very specific reason. We want to maximize the cardiovascular stress of this session rather than loading up your muscular system. But don\u2019t worry, you\u2019ll still feel it in your muscles \u2013 likely all of them.\n\n\u200b\n\nTo keep the total stress of this shorter session fairly high, you\u2019re going to have _just enough_ recovery between each effort, but nothing extra \u2013 so don\u2019t let the short duration fool you into thinking this is going to be easy. On the contrary, you might find this to be one of the more challenging\u2014and productive\u2014sessions in our library. Now, go out there and get that stage win!\n",

                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "In this workout, the shorter the interval duration, the higher the power target will be. Starting from 30 minutes of low Tempo, and finishing with 5-minutes of high-quality MAP work, proper pacing is crucial to success in this workout. While you could easily be above target power for the entire 30-minute effort, that would set you up to fail in the last two efforts. Be smart and pace yourself; you can always go harder in the final 5-minute effort if you want to!\n\n\u200b\n\nAt any intensity above Endurance pace, the longer you ride, the more fatigued you become. Completing the final 5-minute target when fresh would be unpleasant, hitting it after all of these other intervals makes it a near maximal effort. Proper hydration/cooling and nutrition are vital if you want to nail this workout.\n\n\u200b\n\nIf you are preparing for any longer ride/event where you will be required to keep on the gas from start to finish, this is the perfect session for you. Completing these efforts in this order not only gives a great physical training boost, but it also toughens you up mentally. Digging deep when fatigued is the key to good performance over longer distances, so expect to suffer in that final 5-minute effort; it will pay off both mentally and physically!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 4, each unique\n\nRest between sets: 12 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n**Set 1**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n**Set 2 x5**\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n**Set 3**\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8.5 -- 120% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n**Set 4**\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 9.5 -- 180% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n55 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "Tempo efforts are not maximal, and often feel too \"easy\", leading many people to turn a tempo effort into a Sub-Threshold or even Supra-Threshold effort. That is not the point! If we wanted you to go harder, you would see a different workout in your Training Plan. We know you can go harder for 25-minutes, but that is not the point of a Tempo Session.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhat many people don't realize is that your body's ability to process oxygen and metabolites is nearly identical from 80%-100% of FTP. The main change across that intensity range is the rate at which those metabolites are being generated. While you would get a slightly greater training load from doing this session at a higher power, you would be adding more fatigue to your system than we want. That extra fatigue means you either need to ease off your workouts in the days leading up, or ease off your workouts on the days after. From a big picture point of view that's no good! This session gives a great steady-state aerobic training load, while leaving you fresh enough that you can hit training hard the days before and after. That means your training load over the entire week is often higher when you maintain restraint and stick to those Tempo Targets.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 2\n\n**Interval**\n\nWork: 25 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\nRest: 15 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n1 hour 55 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "Just as the name implies, this workout contains 8 3-minute long efforts right at or just below FTP. Looking at power demands alone, you would not expect this session to deliver any real suffering. You would be right. However, in this session, cadence becomes the real money maker.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe odd intervals (1,3,5,7) will require you to ride at an exceptionally low cadence. Just like GOAT, this will stress your muscular system more than your cardiovascular system. The even intervals (2,4,6,8) will require you to ride at 100+ RPM. This has the exact opposite effect, less strain on your muscles, but a greater strain on your cardiovascular system.\nAlternating back and forth between low and high cadence will ensure both your muscular system and cardiovascular system get pushed hard. This workout doesn't stop there; these large swings in cadence targets will also hit your Neuromuscular system. Your nervous system has to switch between recruiting your muscles at maximal force, and then maximal speed.\n\n\nWrapping all of those training benefits into a single workout is what makes this session more than just a set of 3-minute sub-threshold efforts But ONLY if you follow the cadence targets, so don't ignore them!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 4\n\nRest between sets: 2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "This workout combines several technique driven intervals. These will improve your overall form and efficiency on the bike. The first two drills, Cadence Holds and Builds, are designed to improve the way you recruit your leg, glute and core muscles throughout your pedal stroke. They do this by forcing you to sustain a cadence just above 'comfortable' and by pushing you to your maximal cadence.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe last drill, Single Leg Efforts, ask you to unclip one leg and ride at a steady, single-legged effort. This forces you to pull up on the pedal instead of just pushing down and ensures maximal muscle awareness and engagement. This workout is best done while riding indoors on a trainer because even small variations in terrain can affect your ability to properly execute this workout. The majority of this workout is done in heart rate Z1/2 /// 50-75% of threshold /// RPE 2-5. You should keep the effort level below threshold (heart rate Z4, 100% of threshold, RPE 7-8) during the max cadence efforts.\n\n\u200b\n\nWORKOUT GOALS:\n\n- To improve stillness and stability at high cadences.\n- To improve muscle fiber engagement for improved efficiency at all cadences.\n- To increase maximum cadence.\n- To make that pedal stroke as smooth as butter.\n\nCADENCE TARGETS:\n\n- Warm-up 80-90rpm\n- Build: 90-150rpm\n- Hold: 115rpm\n- Single Leg: 85rpm\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 3\n\nRest Between Sets: 8 minutes @ RPE 23 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: N/A\n\n**Interval**\n\n5 seconds @ RPE 5.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 7 --95% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n5 seconds @ RPE 4 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 40% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 7.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 40% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 40% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n8 minutes 15 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "Multiple Run/Bike brick workout\n\nChrysalis is another world first from The Sufferfest. Designed to be performed as four, mini-brick workouts in one session. In order to best execute this workout, you'll utilize a STATIONARY BIKE or TRAINER and a TREADMILL.\\* We recommend using a portable media device; smartphone or tablet, or placing your device where it can be seen from both pieces of equipment. Each bike set consists of 8-minutes of cycling and 4-minutes of running with 30-seconds in between for transitions. After each run, the transition back to the bike is a generous 90-seconds so you can recover just enough to repeat the next block at high intensity.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince this is a No-Vid, you'll have to pay attention to the screen for instructions. Be ready to begin on the treadmill with a short run warmup, then a short bike warmup, which will then take you right into the first bike set of 8-minutes.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe bike sets are set at the normal 4DP values. For the running sets, the number in the power box won't mean anything, so just use the HR zones and RPE metrics for guidance on running intensity. After the 4th run set, you'll stay on the treadmill to cool down with an easy jog/walk.\n\n\\*DON\u2019T HAVE A TREADMILL? It\u2019s not optimal, but you can still use this video by running outside for four minutes. [Instructions on how to use Chrysalis without a treadmill, as well as additional helpful info](https://support.thesufferfest.com/hc/en-us/articles/360001328515-Running-and-Triathlon-Workouts)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up (Run)**\n\n3 minutes 20 seconds @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up (Bike)**\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute 15 seconds @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Bike 1**\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Run 1**\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 While_ Nine Hammers_ packs a huge MAP/FTP punch, it also helps drive up your sustained power regardless of your rider type or weakness. Facing the first 3 hammers gives your aerobic (MAP/FTP) system a hefty load to deal with and will just about fully deplete your AC stores, which makes this the perfect time to start the 2nd set from _The Shovel_. With depleted reserves, starting with the short 5 second sprints ensures that you are just fresh enough to push your NM system but fatigued enough that your AC never fully recovers for the duration of these intervals. With your AC depleted, heart rate pegged, and breathing rate through the roof, the last thing you WANT is the final 2 hammers. This isn't about what you want, though. It's about what you need.\n\n\u200b\n\nBy the time you start this set of hammers, your top-end power will be feeling completely drained; any \"snap\" you might usually rely on to make it through these 3-4 minute efforts will be long gone. The higher your FTP, the faster you will recover, and the higher your MAP, the greater the punishment you can handle.             "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "This workout is another excellent addition to our \"Drills\" series. Over the next 45 minutes, you will complete four 30-second cadence builds, and six 60-second high cadence holds. This workout places a considerable demand on your Neuromuscular System, as your muscles are forced to contract and relax as quickly as possible. At the same time, the shorter recovery period between these drills will keep your heart rate, and breathing rate elevated, giving you a great cardiovascular workload.\n\nLet's breakdown the two drills you will be doing.\n\nCadence Builds: The name of the game here is absolute peak cadence, not peak power. To achieve this, you need to be in a small gear and have very light resistance. Starting at 90-RPM, steadily increase your cadence until you reach your absolute max with about 5-seconds left, and hold that to the end. Your limiting factor on these efforts needs to be leg speed. If resistance/power output is your limiting factor, try starting in an easier gear, or shift into an easier gear 15-seconds in. Bouncing in the saddle is okay for this drill.\n\nCadence Holds: These efforts require you to maintain the highest cadence you can without starting to bounce in the saddle. For some of you that will be 100-RPM, for others, it will be 150-RPM. The key is to settle into YOUR peak sustainable cadence. Like the Builds, the goal here is not high power, so these efforts are limited to 90% of FTP. Do not be surprised if your heart rate is well into Zone 4 by the time you hit the last few holds.\n\nTo properly execute this session, your effort between drills needs to be low. With limited recovery time between these maximal Neuromuscular Efforts, riding above Zone 1 between efforts will only reduce your ability to max out your cadence. While the power targets between are Zone 1, do not be surprised if your heart rate does not drop below Zone 2 after the first couple builds.\n\nWORKOUT GOALS:\n\n- Improved muscle recruitment and firing patterns\n- Improved muscle coordination at higher cadences\n- Deliver a high Neuromuscular and Cardiovascular load while minimizing the power demands placed on your muscles\n- Help you develop a silky smooth pedal stroke\n\nCADENCE TARGETS:\n\n- Warm-up 80-90rpm\n- Build: 90-150rpm\n- Hold: 115rpm\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n6 minutes @ RPE32 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **Number of Sets: 2, each unique\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: N/A\n\n**Set 1: x4**\n\n5 seconds @ RPE 5.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 7 --95% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n5 seconds @ RPE 4 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n**Set 2: x6**\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "The idea behind this session can be seen in Who Dares, Fight Club, and Standing Starts into sustained efforts. Your bodies ability to clear out metabolites and process oxygen is nearly identical between 90% of FTP and 100% of FTP, the difference is that at 100% of FTP your body is producing those metabolites at the same rate it is clearing them. At 90% of FTP your body can clear things at the same rate, but your body isn't producing them at the same rate.\n\n\nLong Sub-Threshold efforts represent an effort that your body can just about handle (assuming you are properly fueled and not completely exhausted), clearing things out faster than they can accumulate. To really stress that clearance rate each of these Sub-Threshold efforts start with a 20-second effort well above FTP. By the time you settle into the Sub-Threshold effort, your body will be flooded with those metabolites that cause your legs and lungs to burn. However, since you are below FTP (clearing things out faster than you are producing them), the concentration of those metabolites will slowly drop over the course of the whole effort. Not only does this train your body to clear things faster, but it will also mentally prepare for the discomfort associated with efforts above FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nFor this session, we are asking you to dance on that razor's edge of your FTP, ideally the side that allows you to complete the session. If your legs or lungs aren't feeling great, you are better off dropping the steady effort by 5% and keeping the starting effort at 100%.\nAnother component of this is settling into a good rhythm of breathing and pedaling. Everyone has a preferred cadence, and this is an instance where your preferred cadence supersedes the cadence targets onscreen. We want you dancing right on that edge of your comfort, and you can get much closer to that edge riding your preferred cadence.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 seconds @ RPE 9.5 -- 180% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n55 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                }

                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness. While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing. Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high and your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week. Shorter Endurance rides (like this one) can fit in both a hard week of training and a recovery week. That is, only if you do it right! Most people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\"\n\nTruth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride, especially one under 90 minutes should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted.\n\nSo what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like? For 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70%, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in low to mid Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can; for most this is 80-90rpm. Also, your RPE should be a 2-4 on a scale of 1-10.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right? It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster, but you will have to trust us on this one! When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions, or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: 4\n\n**Interval**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",

                    ],
                    "body": "The training benefit of this session comes down to the uncomfortably high cadence you need to hold during each effort. Even though these efforts are under FTP, the high leg speed required will leave your system working harder than usual for the required power output.\n\n\nBy maintaining the highest cadence possible (without bouncing in the saddle) you end up pushing your neuromuscular coordination near its limits in a similar way to Cadence Builds.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith an emphasis on low torque (high RPM) efforts this session is polar opposite to sessions like GOAT and Power Station. Even though these efforts are short and below FTP the high cadence places more of a load on your cardiovascular system, so expect your heart rate and breathing to be higher than normal for the power.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince muscles can only contract (pull) any given muscle will primarily move a joint in a single direction. When it comes to pedaling a bike, your quads and glutes can push the pedals down, while your hamstrings and hip flexors pull the pedals back up (with the help of your glutes and quads on the other leg). If you were to pedal with one leg (as you do in Cadence Drills) and your hamstrings and glutes were unable to contract, once you get to the bottom of the pedal stroke your leg would be stuck down there. No matter how hard you might try, your glutes and quads will do nothing to help you get that pedal all the way around. Suppose you do have both feet clipped in, and you are letting your opposite leg push down to bring your leg back up to 12 o'clock. If your quads and glutes are still contracting (pushing the pedal down) while the glutes and quads of your other leg are starting to push their pedal down, you will end up with one leg working against the other. You must relax the glutes and quads of one leg to get all of the power out of the glutes and quads of your other leg.\n\nThis is where neuromuscular coordination comes into play. During each pedal revolution, your legs have to \u201cswitch on\u201d and \u201cswitch off\u201d almost all of the muscles in your legs. By maintaining your highest cadence without bouncing, you are pushing all of the muscles in each leg to contract and relax (switch on and off) as quickly as possible.\n\n\nWhile we give specific cadence targets in this session, everyone has a different limit to what cadence they can maintain before bouncing in the saddle. To get the intended benefit of this session you need to maintain the power targets at the highest cadence that YOU can maintain. For some that might be 105RPM, for others, it might be 150RPM. What matters is that you push YOUR neuromuscular system to its limits.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 7 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "This session is all about high-torque efforts, very similar to the efforts you would experience riding up the steep slopes of Mt Sufferlandria. While these efforts are short and the intensity isn\u2019t too high, the low cadence targets combined with minimal recovery will leave some begging for the high-cadence sprints of _The Omnium_. High-torque efforts like these have two primary benefits: improved neuromuscular coordination and increased muscular endurance.\n\n\u200b\n\nDuring each pedal revolution, your legs have to \u201cswitch on\u201d and \u201cswitch off\u201d almost all of the muscles in your legs. High-cadence efforts in something like _Cadence Builds_ are great for teaching these groups to make that switch quickly. These low-cadence efforts are better for teaching ALL of the muscles in your legs to \u201cswitch on.\u201d Done properly, you should be pulling with your hamstrings with one leg while the other leg is pushing down with all the force your glutes and quads can muster. If you feel like you are pushing yourself up out of the saddle during harder efforts (like seated sprints), your hamstrings are not being utilized since they should pull you back down into your saddle.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe second main benefit is improved muscular endurance. Even though the session is under 45 minutes, **you'll put a similar amount of muscular fatigue into your legs as a steady, multi-hour base ride.** You can almost view this session as hitting the leg press for 8 sets of 100 reps. And just like the weight room, proper form is absolutely key. That means:\n\n- You should focus on pushing down AND pulling back up. You want your glutes and quads activated on the way down and your hamstring and hip flexors activated on the way up.\n- To properly engage your hamstrings think about trying to pulling your heel up to your butt when your crank arm is going from 6 o\u2019clock to 10 o\u2019clock.\n- Your knees should be tracking straight up and down, no collapsing in or out.\n- Your core should be fully engaged to keep your hips steady in the saddle. This will be easier if you are both pushing and pulling during each pedal revolution.\n\nThis session is very similar to _Power Station_. Both help improve your muscular endurance and coordination; the biggest difference is the work to rest ratio between the two. While the intervals here are shorter than those in _Power Station_, the decreased recovery duration means fatigue will build faster, especially for those with a weakness in repeated efforts.\n\nModifying interval length and recovery duration can also be seen between sessions like _Revolver_ and _A Very Dark Place_. Both serve up a healthy dose of MAP/VO2 work, but the overall feeling of those two sessions is different.\n\nIf you find that your lower back starts to ache during this session or that you have to start rocking in the saddle to keep the power up, then it\u2019s time for you to get started on the SYSTM Yoga program.             "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/243a7ecb-49a0-4ebd-a131-5504bfc73435-ISLAGIATT_library.jpg",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "When you want to increase your endurance and add some threshold work but only have two hours, this is the session you need. By adding in multiple surges and short chunks of time above threshold, ISLAGIATT overloads your system with metabolic byproducts ('the nasties'), which your body has to learn to clear out more efficiently.\n\n\u200b\n\nCombining such long interval durations with these hard surges not only forces your body to cope with the effort, but it pushes you harder mentally because after each surge, the effort right at threshold \u201cfeels\u201d harder than it should. With the final intervals focusing more on short, repeated efforts, you'll stress your body's ability to recover when deeply fatigued, making this more than just an \u201cendurance builder\" workout, but one that will help you keep churning out power deep into the final kilometers of challenging rides or events.\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "While the single tempo effort you complete in this session is steady in terms of power, it is the specific cadence targets that set this session apart from other tempo workouts.\n\n\u200b\n\nEven though an effort at 80% of FTP might seem \"easy\" the truth is your body is working at processing oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate when you are right at FTP. The difference is that the overall stress on your system when riding tempo is considerably less than riding at FTP. That means you can either have harder days before or after a tempo session (compared to a Threshold session) or you can increase the duration of those tempo efforts to make the overall training stimulus equal (or greater) than completing several repeats right at your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis tempo effort is divided into 3 segments of equal duration. While the power is the same across all segments, your target cadence starts and low and increases with each new segment. Starting with a long block of low cadence should fatigue your muscles from the start of your effort. As the effort builds and you create more fatigue, the increased cadence targets will place a greater demand on your cardiovascular system. That will, in some way, feel like a nice break given the load you have been putting on your muscular system. The cadence targets in the final segment will force your fatigued muscles to maintain good coordination as the faster cadence requires your muscles to switch \"on\" and \"off\" at a faster rate. Between the low rpm sections, and the high rpm work under fatigue, this tempo session not only helps train your FTP, but it has a training benefit to your neuromuscular system.\n\n\u200b\n\nYou can expect your Heart Rate to remain low for the power targets during the low cadence segment at the start. As the effort progresses and you reach the final 10 minutes of the high rpm segment your heart rate might go over Z3, which is not something to worry about. While this session appears \"easy\" at first glance, don't be surprised if your legs are feeling it the next day.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n25 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: NA\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\nBuild 1: 25 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nBuild 2: 25 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nBuild 3: 25 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",

                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "With repeated 2-minute long MAP intervals, this session can be viewed as a middle ground between Revolver with its 1 minute MAP efforts and Nine Hammers with its 3-4-minute MAP/FTP efforts. The goal of this session is to accumulate a significant amount of time near your VO2max, or the point at which your body is consuming as much oxygen as it possibly can. That means your heart rate and breathing rate will both be near their max by the end of each interval, especially in the final few intervals.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince it takes time for your heart rate and breathing rate to match your effort, for the first part of each interval, you will be tapping into your Anaerobic Capacity to produce the required power. To account for this, we have limited the recovery duration to be equal to the interval duration. Limited recovery ensures that you will drain your Anaerobic Capacity before the end of the intervals, meaning your body will be forced to produce as much power as possible using oxygen. Pushing your aerobic system to its max like this is not just great for improving MAP, but also your FTP. Since MAP limits your FTP, improving your MAP is vital to the continued growth of your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nBy the end of this session, you will have accumulated 20-minutes near your Maximal Aerobic Power, which will leave your legs aching and your lungs burning.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n5minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort** x10\n\nWork: 2 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 95-105%% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\nRest: 2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n50 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Over-Unders are one of those tried and true sessions that folks have been using for years to improve their FTP and get faster.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session works on the same physiological principal as sessions like Who Dares and Fight Club. Those sessions hit you with short efforts well above FTP, followed by longer efforts moderately below FTP.\nThe concept is simple: you alternate blocks of time just below your FTP, with equal duration blocks just above your FTP. For this session, each interval is 8-minutes in length, with 1-minute blocks at 95% of FTP (Under) and 1-minute blocks at 105% of FTP (Over).\n\n\nThe real training benefit comes from that time spent just below FTP trying to \"Recover.\" Physiologically, you train your body to be more efficient when working just below FTP. Mentally, it shows you that you can still \"recover\" (or at least hold on for dear life) as long as you are riding just a little below your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n1 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minutes 15 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP-- HR <80%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 8.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n15 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n15 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 180% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 3\n\nRest Between Sets: 4 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.75 -- 105% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.75 -- 105% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.75 -- 105% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.75 -- 105% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n3 minutes 15 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Tempo sessions are always a great time to work on pace control, especially Tempo efforts longer than 30 minutes. We are taking that pacing demand a bit further in this session by forcing you to slightly increase your effort as time goes on. This is referred to as a \"Negative-Split\", meaning the second half is faster (or you hold a higher power) than the first half.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhile you might question the benefit of doing \"easier\" tempo efforts, the truth is when riding between 80% and 100% of FTP your body processes oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate. Holding a higher power will give you a higher single day training stimulus, but looking at the big picture that can have its drawbacks. Mainly the fatigue those harder sessions cause, which requires easier workouts the days before and after. Sticking to the Tempo targets gets you nearly the same training stimulus while allowing you to hit harder sessions the rest of the week.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session contains a single 60-minute tempo effort, broken into three 20-minute segments. You will spend the first 20-minutes at 80% of FTP, the next 20 at 84%, and the final 20 at 87%. By the time you hit the last 10-minutes of this effort, that 87% will feel much harder than it should. Another way of thinking about this one, if you were to reverse the order, and start at 87%, what you would likely find is that your RPE stays fairly consistent for the entire effort, even though the power targets are dropping.\n\n\u200b\n\nOverheating, not drinking enough, being under-fueled and mental fatigue will all play a factor in how you feel in that final block. They will also impact your heart rate. While these power targets are usually associated with Zone 3 heart rate, many people will see their heart rate climb into low Z4 if they are not hydrating properly, or have inadequate cooling. This can be a great session to act as a \"wake up call\" on any poor training habits you might have so take note and aim to address those issues during your next workout.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: NA\n\nRest between sets: NA\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\n20 minutes@ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n1 hour 15 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "Do you have Couchlandrian Tendencies? This short but powerful workout will cure you of that affliction and reassert your inner Sufferlandrian. The session is based on a combination of specific micro-intervals (made famous by Japanese coach and physiologist Izumi Tabata) that we combined with classic tempo efforts. This gives you a superb mix of Anaerobic Capacity (AC), Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP), and FTP training stresses in one short workout to help you go faster and stay stronger for longer.\n\n\u200b\n\nNow, for the sports science purists among you, the 'Tabata' intervals should actually be named 'Koichi' intervals, since it was Japanese speedskating coach Irisawa Koichi who first employed the use of the 20-seconds on / 10-seconds off intervals that Dr. Izumi then confirmed via physiology lab studies to yield the best mix of maximal aerobic and anaerobic stress among the different on/off protocols that he tested.\n\n\u200b\n\nFor this workout, we have toned down the original intensity of the Tabata intervals to target MAP rather than Anaerobic Capacity in order to be able to complete the 20/10 micro-intervals and then follow the short efforts immediately with sustained 80-100% of FTP intervals to replicate the kind of attack and then settle efforts that are common in cycling races.\n\n\u200b\n\nFrom a physiological perspective, you\u2019ll produce lots of lactate during the micro-intervals. Then the goal of the tempo and FTP efforts is to stress your body\u2019s capacity to clear that lactate as quickly as possible. Effectively, we\u2019re trying to maximize lactate 'flux.' For each successive round of the efforts, you\u2019ll do one less micro-interval, and the tempo efforts will get shorter. But because you\u2019re a Sufferlandrian, they won\u2019t get easier, and the rest between sets will get shorter. The intensity for the tempo efforts will ramp up with each repetition. Fortunately for you, there are only 3 sets of efforts and you\u2019ll be done in just 30 minutes. If you\u2019ve set aside an hour for this workout, you\u2019ll be happy to have those additional 30 minutes for recovery after this session.\n",

With three sets of 15 minutes at tempo effort (alternating between 85 and 75% of FTP in 2-3 minute intervals, you'll end up with 45 minutes of quality aerobic work.             "__typename": "Content",
            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Sustained Efforts",
            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/dc8e763f-60d3-4d5d-91fa-8443db49db58-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "This really is one of the more classic sessions out there. Whether you are a Triathlete, Road Racers, Mountain Biker, or have just flipped through cycling magazines looking at whatever workouts they might suggest in their \"5-workouts to make you faster\" articles.\n\n\nThe reason it's so popular is that it is easy to follow, helps teach good pacing, and gives you a great threshold training stimulus.\n\n\nSo what is it? Well, it's repeated 20-minute blocks at an effort 5-10% below your FTP. In this case, you are looking at three 20-minute blocks at 90% of your FTP, and effort we refer to as \"Sub-Threshold\".\n\n\nMany refer to this intensity as \"Sweet-Spot\", but we prefer Sub-Threshold, as the real key is to never let your power wonder above FTP. The idea behind and Sub-Threshold is to hold an effort just below FTP. This ensures your effort remains at a workout rate you know your body can handle, but an effort that is quite close to an effort you would not be able to handle.\n\n\nThe only way you are going to make it through three of these 20-minute efforts is if you pace yourself properly. Everyone feels just fine for the first 5-minutes of the first effort, and are often tempted to go harder. Do NOT be that person. 99 times out a 100, that person blows up in the second interval, and never even makes to the last 10-minutes. Or they have to ride that second interval at lower power, turning it into a Tempo session, which is not the goal.\n\n\nGetting a sense of how these efforts \"bite\" towards the end is vital to learning how to pace yourself over longer steady state efforts. Whether that is a Time Trial, local Climb, breakaway, Triathlon, or even a good old Power Test. In each of those cases, the pacing is key, seeing how your RPE can steadily climb even though your power remains unchanged.\nSo how do you know if you are doing this one right?\n\n\nAs we said, the first 5-minutes should feel relatively easy. Around that 5-minute mark, your heart rate should stop climbing, and settle into 2-5% below your LTHR. If your heart rate is climbing for the entire effort and goes above your LTHR, then you are going too hard.\n\n\nIf you hit the 10-minute mark, your legs feel fine, and your heart rate is still in Zone 3, then you aren't going hard enough.\nIf you have never done a session like this before, you can consider only doing the first 20minute effort, or even sticking to just the first 15 of each effort. There is no shame in building up to this full session, so don't be afraid to pause and fast forward as needed.\n\n\nNailing this session is really about getting in tune with your body, and understanding what that edge feels like, between a sustainable and an unsustainable effort.\n\n\nThat means failing this workout is fairly common, and not at all something to get down about. As long as you learn your lesson, like what \"too hard\" feels like 10-minutes in, then you have bettered your riding ability, even if this workout itself was not executed successfully.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 15 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n12 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/0bfe6ac9-cd44-4ee5-b701-c8b7c918d0b6-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Just like Fight Club and Who Dares, this session is all about surging well above threshold, and then trying to recover without dropping your power anywhere close to your recovery zone. The 2 things that make this session stand out are:\n\n1. You only have one single continuous effort (which happens to be 60-minutes in length)\n2. Your recovery power is low Tempo, which is good because any higher than that and you wouldn't last the full 60 minutes!\n\nAs you increase intensity from 80% of FTP up to 100% of FTP, your legs begin to produce more and more metabolites, but the rate at which your body CAN clear them is almost the same. As you close in on 100% of FTP you suddenly are at a point where production of metabolites equals your clearance rate. Now move just a bit over FTP and those metabolites are going to continue to build until you drop your effort back below FTP.\n\n\nTo improve your bodies clearance rate for those metabolites, you need to spend a decent amount of time with more of those metabolites in your system than your bodies current clearance rate can handle.\n\n\nThat is what this session is all about, short hard efforts above FTP to build an excess of metabolites, followed by steady riding at 80% of FTP. This steady-state effort between surges is high enough that your body will still be working at max clearance rates but low enough that you can keep doing those surges over and over again, which is good for you because this is not a short interval.\n\n\nWhile you can achieve the same training stimuli by holding shorter blocks above FTP, those sessions have their drawbacks. The main one is nailing the exact right intensity above FTP that will allow you to accumulate enough time in that metabolite flooded state. While we like to think our FTP is set in stone, the reality is it can fluctuate from day to day, which makes finding that balancing point for a session like that so difficult. You can easily go too hard and blow up early, or not go hard enough and never really push that clearance rate to the max. By hitting surges well above FTP, then holding an effort a good deal below FTP, any day to day variation in your FTP becomes less of an issue because you never have to dance 5W above or below it.\n\n\nThe added benefit to this Surge and Settle workout style is the boost it can give to your Anaerobic Capacity. An improved AC means you can recover faster, not just from sprint type efforts, but from repeated MAP and FTP efforts as well.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n40 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 12\n\nRest between sets: 4 minutes 40 seconds @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n20 seconds @ RPE 8.5 -- 120% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n1 hour 35 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

                }

While it's not as comprehensive or as accurate as our main fitness test, _Full Frontal_, it's far more approachable and easier to pace for new riders. It also doesn't require any special preparation. You just need to feel relatively fresh.\n\n\u200b\n\nBased on more than a year of research (and after dozens of lab tests and thousands of online tests) and using sophisticated analysis of power and heart rate data, _Half Monty_ is far more accurate and comprehensive than standard ramp tests.\n\n\u200b\n\nIt also tells you more about who you are as an athlete. _Half Monty_ provides you with your FTP, Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP), and Cycling Threshold Heart Rate (cTHR), all of which we use to personalize your workout targets.\n\n\u200b\n\nIf you're still using the 4DP estimates when you set up your account, _Half Monty_ will also refine your AC and NM estimates (but will not do so if you've done _Full Frontal_ or manually adjusted your estimates).                             "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "With a total of only nine minutes spent at or near MAP, this session isn't really designed to push you to your limits (that's what Nine Hammers is for). Instead, it's intended to be used as you begin tapering for an event or test day. While the 3-minute MAP efforts are by no means easy, there are only 3 efforts, with nice long 7-minute recoveries between them. What that means is you will be close to fully recovered at the start of each MAP effort.\n\nUnless you have a substantial VO2 weakness, this session won't do much to help improve your MAP. It will, however, help you maintain your current level. There is just enough sting in this workout to get your system working near its max, but not enough time near your max to add much fatigue. Regardless of what event you are targeting (with the exception of a flying 200m or Kilo on the track) this should be one of your go-to sessions in the final 10 days of your preparation since it primes your cardiovascular system to help you produce power with oxygen more effectively.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhile ERG mode is great for many workouts, this is one that you might want to run in Level mode, especially if your training has been going well or your Full Frontal results are more than 2 months old. The benefit of this session comes from your body just about hitting its max for the final 10-30 seconds of each effort. Follow the targets set for the first 3-minute interval, and then make any necessary changes to the intensity for the final two.\n\n\u200b\n\nEven though there are cadence targets for each section, you should aim for the same cadence you would hold during the 5-minute test in Full Frontal. The goal is to strike a balance between your cardiovascular system and your muscular system. If your cadence is too low, you will be putting too much stress on your muscular system. Too high and you will be pushing your cardiovascular system more than necessary. If you are relatively fresh, this is how you should feel by the end of each effort:\n\n1. Your heart rate should be above your LTHR.\n2. Your breathing rate should be near its max.\n3. Your legs should be hurting.\n\nThat said, you shouldn't feel like you are turning yourself inside out to make it through the final 30 seconds. Save that feeling for Nine Hammers.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nWork: 3 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 95-105%% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\nRest: 7 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/3e1a4f0e-87f3-4d8d-aa4d-0084c8498e50-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "This brutal but straightforward workout is perfect for developing both FTP and MAP while teaching you a Negative Split pacing strategy. For this workout, you will complete a series of 6-minute efforts. The first 4-minutes are right at your FTP, which isn't so tough in itself, but the final 2-minutes of each effort are set above 90% of MAP.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhen we talk about a \"negative split\" we mean completing the second half of an effort at a higher speed/power than the first half. By the time you hit the MAP portion of each interval, your heart rate and breathing rate will already be nice an high. This limits the AC demand of a standalone MAP effort, where you have a large lag time between producing the power requirement, and your body delivering the oxygen needed to hold that power. Usually, that lag time between oxygen demand oxygen supply is covered by your AC. Paced correctly, your heart rate should essentially be increasing for the entire 6-minutes, as it will be settling into LTHR right as you up the power output.\n\n\u200b\n\nAs you complete each effort, holding 100% of FTP will feel harder and harder. This in itself is excellent mental practice for \"feeling\" how your RPE for the same power can drift up as fatigue sets in. Knowing what 100% of FTP feels like when your legs are nearly spent is a great reminder of why starting an effort too hard will bite you in the end.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis workout ends up delivering a fantastic aerobic workload as you complete 12-minutes of MAP work with minimal help from your AC. Making this an excellent session for those who have a strong AC, but weak MAP. You also rack up 24-minutes at 100% of FTP, which by itself would be a good training load. Add in these MAP efforts, and you multiply the training impact of those 24-minutes.\n\n\u200b\n\nRegardless of your chosen discipline or event, this is a session that will benefit everyone, both regarding learning good pacing and giving your aerobic system a big training boost.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 8 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort** x2\n\nNumber of sets:\n\nRest between sets: 30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: 3\n\n**Interval **\n\nEffort 1: 4 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\nEffort 2: 2 minutes @ RPE 8.5 -- 120% of FTP -- HR >105%%\n\nRest: 5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n50 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minute @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "This is a session that you'll want to complete in Level, rather than Erg, mode. The only time we would suggest Erg mode is if you are unable to maintain the lower power targets set between sprints.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith short maximal sprint efforts, you'll recruit every muscle fiber you have in your legs each effort. While cadence builds force your muscles to contract and relax as quickly as possible, this session forces your muscles to contract with maximal force. Just like cadence builds this session becomes one of the best ways to train your neuromuscular system. Even if your target event does not require you to complete maximal sprints, there is a substantial trickle-down effect to the longer duration power efforts when you train your neuromuscular system.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session is a great alternate to cadence builds or standing starts for those completing our SUF Strength sessions. On days you complete off the bike strength work you want your on bike training to complement the suffering you put yourself through off the bike. That means short maximal efforts (whether for power or for cadence) are the best workouts to complement the strength gains you've made off the bike.\n\n\u200b\n\nAs long as you run this session in slope mode you can complete the sprints either seated or out of the saddle. For those competing in events that do not require much (if any) standing (such as Time Trials or Triathalons) you should complete this sprints seated (and in the aerobars or drops if that is where you are racing).\n\n\u200b\n\nYou should also do these efforts seated if you don't feel an out-of-the-saddle maximal sprint is stable/safe to do on your trainer. Regardless of using ERG or Slope mode, you do not want to hold anything back on any sprint. Seeing your peak power drop as the session goes on is totally normal as your legs fatigue. This is where RPE really becomes the most important metric, rather than power, heart rate, or cadence. Now get on that bike and CRUSH IT!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 18\nRest between sets: 9 minutes 50 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 10 -- 200% of FTP -- >105%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "_Standing Starts_ closely simulates a lifting session on the bike because it requires the engagement of your core, upper body, and lower body. It trains your ability to generate force through the pedals by ensuring you recruit ALL of your muscles to get those cranks turning. No matter your preferred discipline, these efforts are key to teaching your body to recruit all of the muscle fibers in your legs.\n\n\u200b\n\nAll of the benefits in this session come from hitting these 20-second efforts as hard as you possibly can. To do that, you need full recovery between each sprint, and you need to respect that recovery. These efforts should see you start at super low RPMs with very high torque. As you start and increase the effort, your cadence will naturally increase. **Your goal is to get your cadence as high as possible by the end of each 20-second effort.** To maximize your muscle recruitment, you want to both push down and pull up on the pedals at the start. Proper core engagement is a must - your legs need a good strong backboard to push against.\n\n\u200b\n\nWe understand that not everyone's trainer has the necessary resistance or the required stability to perform this workout as described. If you can't safely stand up, then you can get much of the same benefit by doing these efforts seated. If your trainer can\u2019t handle the rapid change in speed or does not have high enough resistance at a super low cadence, then you can start the efforts at a higher cadence and treat them as \u201cnormal\u201d all-out sprints.\n",
