                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Most people who have read or talked about High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT) have probably heard the term \"Tabata\" being thrown around, and for good reason. In the mid 90's Professor Izumi Tabata set out to study the training impact of HIIT compared to a more traditional lower intensity high volume training. While both groups saw a similar increase in VO2max, only the HIIT group improved their Anaerobic Capacity, which is often associated with an increased ability to repeat hard efforts.\n\n\nThe HIIT protocol that Professor Izumi Tabata used was 4-minute blocks broken into what we refer to as \"Micro-Intervals\" 20sec efforts well above VO2max power (similar to what we refer to as MAP) and 10 seconds of recovery.\nThis was one of the first widely recognized studies that promoted HIIT, and since HIIT is The Sufferfest's Specialty, we would be crazy not to include this session.\n\n\nDuring this session, you are looking at 3 sets of Micro-Intervals in 5-minute blocks, with each 20sec power target exceeding 100% of your MAP. While the targets we have set are slightly lower than Tabata's original study, those subjects only completed one 4-minute block of their high-intensity session, and you get to complete 3 of them! That means if you finish the first set feeling fine, increase MAP intensity by 5%, or just switch to slope mode and get back to using RPE; these are MAX intervals after all, so just give it what you've got!\n\n\nThis session really does pack a punch, and being mentally prepared for it is more important than being physically prepared. By design, this session will completely drain your AC and max out your aerobic system. No one gets to that point and feels \"good.\" You need to mentally brace yourself to get into the hurt locker and stay down there until the bitter end.\n\n\nUncertain if you have that mental toughness or skill set to handle this session? Then check out the \"Getting Positive\" module on our Mental Toughness Program. While we encourage everyone to try MTP from start to finish (which takes about 10 weeks) just doing this one module can be incredibly beneficial.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n45 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 3 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: 10\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

There is a reason this simple session has stuck around: it works.\n\n\u200b\n\n30 seconds into a high-intensity effort, enough of your anaerobic energy sources have been depleted that your body shifts to producing that power aerobically. Follow that effort with only 60 seconds of recovery, and your body hasn\u2019t fully replenished those anaerobic stores, meaning it will have to produce that power aerobically after just 25 seconds.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith a total of just 15 (cough, cough) efforts, you will have not only forced your body to replenish its Anaerobic Capacity (AC) over and over, but you've just spent several minutes producing lots of power with lots of oxygen.                     "body": "The ability to hit a given power target right on the nose is one of the hallmarks of a great rider, and that is exactly what you are being forced to do with this session. Each interval has 4 distinct stair steps, increasing slightly with each step. This requires you to finesse your output multiple times for each effort to really feel the difference 10 watts makes.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe stair-step approach also forces your body into a constant state of \u201ccatching up.\u201d Just as your aerobic system settles into the oxygen demands of each effort, you're forced to go harder, which makes you dip back into anaerobic energy systems while your aerobic system catches up. This process constantly forces your anaerobic and aerobic systems to make adjustments. If you're trying to get over a plateau or feel like you're not getting faster, this can be exactly what you need.\n\n\u200b\n\nUnlike other sessions, three of the four sprint efforts come in the first half. This means your legs will be fresh enough so you can go full gas and hit your Neuromuscular (NM) system hard. Not bad for a session that is predominantly focused on building your Anaerobic Capacity (AC) and Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP).\n",

While the first few efforts in each set will feel \"easy,\" since these blocks are stretched out to 8-minutes in length, you will be deep into the red by the end of each set.\n\nWhile the efforts aren't continuous, they are long enough that you will accumulate plenty of time near your VO2max, which is the goal of any MAP workout.                     "body": "This is a session that you'll want to complete in Level, rather than Erg, mode. The only time we would suggest Erg mode is if you are unable to maintain the lower power targets set between sprints.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith short maximal sprint efforts, you'll recruit every muscle fiber you have in your legs each effort. While cadence builds force your muscles to contract and relax as quickly as possible, this session forces your muscles to contract with maximal force. Just like cadence builds this session becomes one of the best ways to train your neuromuscular system. Even if your target event does not require you to complete maximal sprints, there is a substantial trickle-down effect to the longer duration power efforts when you train your neuromuscular system.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session is a great alternate to cadence builds or standing starts for those completing our SUF Strength sessions. On days you complete off the bike strength work you want your on bike training to complement the suffering you put yourself through off the bike. That means short maximal efforts (whether for power or for cadence) are the best workouts to complement the strength gains you've made off the bike.\n\n\u200b\n\nAs long as you run this session in slope mode you can complete the sprints either seated or out of the saddle. For those competing in events that do not require much (if any) standing (such as Time Trials or Triathlons) you should complete these sprints seated (and in the aerobars or drops if that is where you are racing).\n\n\u200b\n\nYou should also do these efforts seated if you don't feel an out-of-the-saddle maximal sprint is stable/safe to do on your trainer. Regardless of using ERG or Slope mode, you do not want to hold anything back on any sprint. Seeing your peak power drop as the session goes on is totally normal as your legs fatigue. This is where RPE really becomes the most important metric, rather than power, heart rate, or cadence. Now get on that bike and CRUSH IT!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 10\n\nRest between sets: 5 minutes 50 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 10 -- 200% of FTP -- >105%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "When it comes to \"peaking\", or performing at your absolute best on a given day, the key is nailing your Taper. The term \"Taper\" refers to how you train in the week or so before your target event to ensure you deliver your best performance. Generally, tapering means reducing your total training volume but continuing to hit some high-intensity efforts. While there are individual variations in the best way to taper, this session has been used by countless professionals leading into the biggest races of their lives -- athletes like World Champions Rohan Dennis and Flora Duffy.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith 3 sets of micro-intervals (40/20s, 30/30s, and 20/40s) you will hit your system with just enough intensity to keep your legs sharp and responsive, without adding any real fatigue. Outside of those 3 sets of micro-intervals, this session is purposefully short and easy. This is a preparation session, not a training session! After all, your event is just around the corner and all of the important training is behind you. Riding harder or longer today will do absolutely nothing to increase your fitness by event day; in fact, all that would do is increase your fatigue, which will only hurt your performance. Rather, this session makes sure your body is humming along and ready to perform on the big day.\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Yep, there are good chunks of sub-threshold in here. But what makes this session special are the surges above threshold during each effort. Your body's ability to clear metabolites and process oxygen doesn't really change at 90% of FTP and above. What that means it that whether you are at 90% or 100% of FTP your body is clearing those things out at the same rate. It's just that at FTP your body is producing more of those metabolites that it is capable of clearing.\n\n\u200b\n\nBy surging above FTP you are creating metabolites faster than your body can clear them. If you were to settle into 100% of FTP, you would only be clearing things out at the rate you are producing them. That means whatever you have produced from that surge will just stay there. By dropping just below FTP your body is clearing things out faster than you are producing them. That means that the excess you got from that surge will slowly be cleared out.\n\n\u200b\n\nEach a surge pops up during this workout, your body should have just about cleared what was made from the last surge. Not only does this push your body's ability to clear these things to the max, but it also teaches your mind to deal with the discomfort of burning lungs and legs associated with these efforts at or above threshold.\n\n\u200b\n\nA simpler way to think of this is that you are teaching your body and mind to \"recover\" just below FTP. Not only does this help bump up your FTP, but it also helps you recover that much faster anytime you let off the gas, whether for a downhill, turn, or finding a good draft. Having the confidence that you can recover while feeling so uncomfortable can mean the difference between hanging onto to a new personal best and completely throwing in the towel.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis is the perfect session to practice your positive thinking from the Mental Toughness Program (If you haven't checked that out already you definitely should!).\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nRest between sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: 4\n\n**Interval **\n\nWork: 30 seconds @ RPE 8.5 -- 120% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\nSteady: 2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n25 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "You can never have too many tools in the shed. After years of lobbying, we finally convinced Grunter von Agony to share his favorite set of implements with us: the fabled _14 Vise Grips_. Taken individually, each of the 14 intervals might appear tame, incapable of inflicting a significant squeeze. But when expertly applied in the correct order, they apply just the right kind of pressure to turn a Couchlandrian into a Sufferlandrian, just like turning coal into diamonds.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhile the duration of each Vise Grip varies (from 30 seconds to 2 minutes), the power targets and recovery durations between them remain constant. The first 30-second interval should feel like a Sunday stroll in the park, but by the end of the first 2-minute Vise Grip, you'll be cursing Grunter's name. As the intervals get shorter, time will appear to stretch. That final 30-second effort will feel like an eternity. When you roll up to the second set, you'll know what you're in for, so just put your head down and prepare yourself to crush or be crushed.\n\n\u200b\n\nOnce you make it through all 14 Vise Grips, you will have been north of your Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP) for a total of 16 minutes. Changing the duration of the efforts (while keeping the same recovery) stresses your Anaerobic Capacity (AC) in a more dynamic way than, say, a more straightforward on/off session like _Half is Easy_. Since the longer efforts have the same recovery duration as the shorter ones, you will eventually deplete your AC, forcing your body to rely on your MAP to hit the required power targets. As the intervals get shorter in the second half of each set, you'll find that you have just enough left in the tank to complete the next effort.\n\n\u200b\n\nUltimately this workout combines the advantages of shorter, higher-power intervals with longer recovery (great for building muscular strength) with the advantages of longer, higher-power intervals with inadequate recovery (great for driving up your MAP and improving your AC).\n",

            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/e984369d-0ef6-4351-bcb3-d8e4ef0b572c-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "There's no getting around the fact that this is a profoundly unpleasant session that will leave your legs feeling like jelly.\nThis session is similar to The Trick, with a few differences. On the plus side, all of the efforts are 15-seconds shorter than those in The Trick. To make up for this, we added two more intervals to this session, bringing the total to 6. That means by the end of this session you will have plowed through 4.5-minutes of AC work.\n\n\nThis workout is one of the few sessions that we do NOT recommend you complete in ERG mode if you are on a smart trainer. The goal is to hold onto the highest power you can for the full 45-seconds. Inevitably in the later sets, your power will dip before you reach the end of the interval. What we want is for you to complete every effort having given everything for 45-seconds. We don't want ERG mode grinding you to a halt because you cannot maintain the (ridiculously) high power targets. Even if you drop down below FTP in the final 10-seconds of these efforts, as long as you are going flat out, you are doing it correctly.\n\nJust take this session one interval at a time, and focus on giving your all for this one effort. You can worry about the others when you get to them. These short efforts with minimal recovery deplete your anaerobic gas tank, forcing your body to get better at producing power aerobically. Your body then starts to ramp up your oxygen intake in order to produce more of the power requirements aerobically.                     "body": "By the end of this session, you will have accumulated 20-minutes at roughly 100% of your MAP. However, that accumulated time is split up over two sets of 5 efforts, each 2-minutes in length. The goal of this session is to accumulate a significant amount of time near VO2max, or the point at which your body is consuming as much oxygen as it possibly can. That means your heart rate and breathing rate will both be near their max by the end of the 4th and 5th interval in each set.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince it takes time for your heart rate and breathing rate to match your effort, for the first part of each interval, you will be taping into your Anaerobic Capacity to produce the required power. Limited recovery ensures that your Anaerobic Capacity is drained before the end of either set, forcing your body to produce as much power as possible aerobically. By splitting these efforts into two sets, you will be producing more power anaerobically compared to doing all ten intervals in a single set. While this means you accumulate less time near your VO2max, you will be able to hold a higher power for the final five intervals. Splitting the efforts will shift the training stress away from your cardiovascular system and onto your muscular system.\n\nUltimately this session will improve your ability to produce power aerobically in addition to improving your muscular strength and endurance, both of which are key to increasing your MAP and your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n5minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 2\n\nRest between sets: 20 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: 5\n\n**Interval**\n\nWork: 2 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 95-105%% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\nRest: 2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

            "__typename": "Content",
            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Technique & Drills",
            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/27a5d0ee-7bbe-4b37-96bb-1c9258996e65-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "We understand that not everyone's trainer has the necessary resistance, or the required stability to perform this workout as described. For stability issues you can get much of the same benefit by doing these efforts seated. If your trainer can\u2019t handle the rapid change in speed, or does not have high enough resistance at a super low cadence then you can start the efforts at a higher cadence and simply treat them as \u201cnormal\u201d all out sprints.",
                            "severity": "Information"
                        },
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "In this session, you will be going straight from a max 20-second high torque starting effort into 40 seconds right at MAP. The Starting effort should just about completely drain your Anaerobic Capacity, which will leave you gasping for air as you start each 40-second MAP effort. By forcing yourself to maintain MAP after a maximal sprint, you are asking your body to increase oxygen supply to your muscles as quickly as possible by increasing your heart rate and breathing rate. Being able to increase oxygen consumption rapidly means your body will better handle changes in pace both above and below threshold.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhat you need to do:\n\n- You will need to begin each Standing Start at super low RPM's with very high torque (high resistance). To maximize muscle recruitment you want to both push-down and pull-up on the pedals at the start. Proper core engagement is a must, as your legs need a sturdy backboard to push against.\n- You'll want the starting resistance to be just high enough that only your max effort can get the pedals moving; after those first few revs your goal is to get your cadence up as high as possible by the end of the 20 seconds. The best way to ensure you have the right resistance is to complete this session in slope mode rather than ERG mode.\n- Once the 20-second start is over you want to settle right into the 40-second effort at MAP, avoiding any significant drop in power at the transition point. Since the goal of this 40-second MAP effort is maximal cardiovascular demand, aim to hold your cadence 10-15 RPM higher than you would for the 5-minute test in Full Frontal.\n\nFor Time Trialists and Triathletes:\n\nAfter the Standing Start, you will want to get into your aerobars and hold the same position you will be competing in. Those on regular road bikes should get down into the drops.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n15 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 5\n\nRest between sets: 15 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 seconds @ RPE 10 -- 180% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n40 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 95-105%% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/9386c2fc-486c-4225-bf9f-7dc8a5062cd5-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "While some of you will know this intensity level as \"Sweet-Spot\", we prefer the name Sub-Threshold, because we want to drive home the fact that you should keep your power below FTP. In the same way that longer Tempo efforts can feel \"easy,\" these shorter Sub-Threshold efforts can also feel \"easy\". After all, if you can hold 100% of FTP for about an hour, then holding less than that for 5-minutes should be a piece of cake right? We know you can go harder for 5-minutes, but that is not what we are asking for.\n\n\nThis session is not intended to push you to your limits, nore is it designed to be a massive training load. The real purpose is to essentially keep your fatigue levels right where they are, by giving your body just enough intensity to ensure that you are not \"more recovered\" after today.\n\n\nWhile some folks will say that there is no training benefit to such short Sub-Threshold efforts, when viewed in a bigger picture sense (like a 3-week training block) they can be the perfect efforts to ensure you get the most out of a longer training block.\n\n\nWe would even ask that you view this session as more of an assessment, rather than strictly a workout. That's because you should be comparing this power output to heart rate response and your own internal RPE. When you have heavy fatigue, your heart rate will struggle to hit its normal peaks. When fresh you would be getting into Z4 heart rate by the end of the last two intervals, and your RPE should never really climb above a 7. When holding onto excess fatigue, your heart rate won't climb above Z3, and your RPE will be above an 8. At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.\n\n\nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 5\n\nRest between sets: 5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n35 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "While you're certainly going to feel this workout in your legs, it's what happens in your head over these six intervals that matter most. A sort of 'Applied Mental Training Program' session is a unique addition to the SUF library.\n\n\u200b\n\nOver the course of the workout, you'll be taken through six different mental toughness tasks drawn from the SYSTM Mental Training Program (available here in the app). We'll teach you how to focus, use positive self-talk, and see an image of Future You to help you push through the Suffering.\n\n\u200b\n\nFrom a physical point of view, this is a series of five-minute intervals with very high Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP) efforts at both ends. They pack the same training punch as much longer Sub-Threshold efforts with the added bonus of stimulating your MAP and Anaerobic Capacity (AC) simultaneously.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Physiologically**:\nThe first 30-second effort digs you into an anaerobic hole. Even though it is a MAP-based target, your heart rate and breathing rates (and thus ability to deliver oxygen) are still low, so your body must produce much of this power anaerobically. By the time you settle into the 4-minutes at just below FTP, your body will have produced an excess of metabolites responsible for that burning in your legs. Only by riding below FTP will your body clear them out since FTP is the tipping point where your body produces metabolites at the same rate it is clearing them. By holding you at FTP, your body cannot clear out that excess, forcing you to deal with the associated discomfort for the next 4-minutes.\n\nCapping the effort off with a final 30-second surge requires that you dig into what is left of your AC while your body pushes you close to your VO2 max, or the point at which your body is using as much oxygen as it possibly can. The net result is a session that is great for improving FTP, MAP, and AC, regardless of your strengths and weaknesses.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Psychologically**:\nEach 4-minute segment at just below FTP will end up feeling harder than it should, given your body is forced to stew in whatever excess metabolites you produced in the first 30-seconds. While it will be unpleasant, you should find it never really gets MORE unpleasant. In addition to the benefits from the actual mental training exercises, this preps you to have confidence in your ability to hold longer sustained FTP efforts. The final surge then shows you that even when you feel uncomfortable for that long, your body still has something more to give. Going through the Mental Training techniques while you're pushing through the discomfort will only make you stronger out on the road.\n\n\u200b\n\nIn some cultures, the bat symbolizes the death of old ways and the rise of new ones. Time to burn those old, bad habits and build some new, positive ones.\n",

You'll start with a short max effort from a standstill, recover, then have four 30-second low cadence MAP efforts with a generous 90 seconds of recovery between each. It's rare for Sir Neal to allow you so much recovery, but you'll deplete your Creatine Phosphate and muscle glycogen stores within these 30s efforts so it's crucial that your muscles have enough time to recover the necessary energy to repeat each successive interval with the same strength. By the end of this workout, you may feel as though you've done a heavy leg session in the gym, as this type of workout recruits primarily your Type II and Type IIb muscle fibers and leaves your slow-twitch fibers relatively fresh.  \n",

                    "body": "This session packs a punch with eight 3-minute intervals, all starting at 100% of FTP, and ending at 100% of MAP. Not only is this a great workout physiologically, but it's also great for learning how to ride a negative split.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhen we talk about a \"negative split\" we mean completing the second half of an effort at a higher speed/power than the first half. While the first few of these might not feel so bad, the repetition and 1:1 work to recovery will ensure your heart rate and breathing stay elevated for the second half.\n\n\u200b\n\nAs you complete each effort, holding 100% of FTP will feel harder and harder. This in itself is excellent mental practice for \"feeling\" how your RPE for the same power can drift up as fatigue sets in. Knowing what 100% of FTP feels like when your legs are nearly spent is a great reminder of why starting an effort too hard will bite you in the end.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis dishes out a respectable 24-minutes of intensity. The fact that your heart and lungs are already pumping at high output when you start each MAP effort maximizes the gain you'll get from those 8-minutes at 100% of MAP.\n\n\u200b\n\nRegardless of your chosen discipline or event, this is a session that will benefit everyone, both regarding learning good pacing and giving your aerobic system a big training boost.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 8 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort** x8\n\nEffort 1: 2 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\nEffort 2: 1 minutes @ RPE 8.5 -- 120% of FTP -- HR >105%%\n\nRest: 3 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minute @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n",

The workout includes:\n\n- **Mobility exercises for the hips, mid-back, and shoulders** in order to activate muscles, increase range of motion, and prevent injury. For example, the shoulder internal rotation strengthens the high elbow catch position, while the shoulder external rotation strengthens the rotator cuff muscles and allows for proper movement of the arm overhead.  \n- **Kicking on your side** to maintain the strength and endurance needed to apply pressure to the water on both the downstroke and upstroke of the kick.  \n- **\u201cSwimming\u201d with a band.** Maintaining the specific muscle endurance required for swimming is exceptionally difficult without actually swimming, but performing the movement pattern, even without a band or one arm at a time, is a great way to maintain some of the muscle conditioning that you\u2019ve already developed.  \n- **Isometric exercises** increase neuromuscular activation and provide the muscles with more time under tension, or the amount of time that they\u2019re in the contracted state.  \n",

                    "body": "These two mini Pyramids of Power might remind you of The Shovel... This one, however is a little less focused on Anaerobic Capacity and a little more on muscle endurance, due to that big blue block in the middle. The first pyramid will begin to fatigue your muscles and tax your AC before you face 20 minutes at tempo. With both of those efforts under your belt, the second pyramid will drain the rest of your AC and ask your aerobic system to pick up the slack. This might even feel similar to a mountain bike or cyclocross race effort- you take it out hard, jockeying for the hole shot or a front pack position before getting into the technical elements. Then you settle into a sustainable effort for a short while, maybe working with a couple others before battling it out for your final finishing position.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n9 minutes @ RPE             "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Most people who have read or talked about High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT) have probably heard the term \"Tabata\" being thrown around, and for good reason. In the mid 90's Professor Izumi Tabata set out to study the training impact of HIIT compared to a more traditional lower intensity high volume training. While both groups saw a similar increase in VO2max, only the HIIT group improved their Anaerobic Capacity, which is often associated with an increased ability to repeat hard efforts.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe HIIT protocol that Professor Izumi Tabata used 4-minute blocks broken into what we refer to as \"Micro-Intervals\" 20sec efforts well above VO2max Power (similar to what we refer to as MAP) and 10 seconds of recovery.\nThis was one of the first widely recognized studies that promoted HIIT, and since HIIT is The Sufferfest's Specialty, we would be crazy not to include this session, which rounds out our series of Micro-Interval workouts, which already includes 40/20's and 20/10's.\n\n\u200b\n\nDuring this session, you are looking at 3 sets of Micro-Intervals in 11-minute blocks, with each 30sec power target at or just below 100% of your MAP.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session really does pack a punch, and being mentally prepared for it is more important than being physically prepared. By design, this session will completely drain your AC and max out your aerobic system. No one gets to that point and feels \"good.\" You need to mentally brace yourself to get into the hurt locker and stay down there until the bitter end.\n\n\u200b\n\nUncertain if you have that mental toughness or skill set to handle this session? Then check out the \"Getting Positive\" module on our Mental Toughness Program. While we encourage everyone to try MTP from start to finish (which takes about 10 weeks) just doing this one module can be incredibly beneficial.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n15 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n1 minute 45 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: 15\n\n**Interval**\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n15 seconds @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "This tempo session may not look very tough, but take a look at the recovery intervals...you only get 3 minutes at 65%. That's not a leisurely pace, which means that you'll go into the next 7 minute build with some fatigue still in the legs. The combination of partial recoveries and effort building intervals will leave you feeling like you've done more than 21 minutes at tempo by the end. The build format of each of the 7-minute efforts is also great for working on your negative split pacing which is great for everyone, but especially important if you're a time trialist or triathlete. With nice long ramps to warmup and cool down, you should feel good going into the main set and be able to recover fairly quickly when finished.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n10 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 3 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n**Interval **\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

        {
            "__typename": "Content",
            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Sustained Efforts",
            "channel": "MvDmhsvEBR",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/472a93e0-3082-4c8d-a5ba-12f770db475b-Attacker_library.jpg",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "Being able to finish strong comes from properly pacing your efforts and preparing to finish strong. This session is all about improving those abilities. For just over 50 minutes, you'll tackle five different 6-minute long, progressive efforts that start just below FTP and finish well above it for the final minute.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe real challenge of this workout is the limited 1-minute recovery sections between each effort. You\u2019ll want to savor every second of those short recoveries. This workout will help improve your FTP and improve your ability to recover while pushing just under your threshold for the first half of each effort. You\u2019ll also learn to manage your pacing and put out power above your threshold after holding steady just below that breakpoint.\n\n\u200b\n\nRiders with sustained weakness will benefit greatly from this workout, as will anyone looking to push up their FTP.\n\n_Attacker_ is quite similar to the SUF workout, _Defender._ However, the efforts within each interval are 2-minutes shorter, and instead of starting harder and backing off like in _Defender,_ the efforts in this session start controlled and keep squeezing harder and harder until the end.\n",

            "__typename": "Content",
            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Sustained Efforts",
            "channel": "MvDmhsvEBR",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.amazonaws.com/content/1eae2599-0ade-4a35-896e-44113a3b2fea-Cobbler_library.jpg",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "The 3x25-minute sub-threshold workout is one of the most classic interval sessions out there, so it felt natural to use the Queen of the Classics as the scene for this FTP-builder. The reason the 3x25 sub-threshold workout is so popular is that it is easy to follow, helps teach good pacing, and gives you a great threshold training stimulus.\n\n\u200b\n\nIn this case, you're looking at three, 25-minute blocks at around 90% of your FTP, an effort we refer to as \"Sub-Threshold\".\n\nMany refer to this intensity as \"Sweet-Spot\", but we prefer Sub-Threshold, as the real key is to never let your power creep above your FTP. Staying just below threshold ensures that your effort remains at an intensity you know your body can handle but that is close to what would not be sustainable.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe only way you're going to make it through three of these 25-minute efforts is if you pace yourself properly. Everyone feels just fine for the first 5 minutes of the first effort, and are often tempted to go harder. Don't be that person. More often than not, that person blows up spectacularly in the second interval, unable to finish the session. Or they have to ride that second interval at lower power, turning it into a Tempo session, which is not the goal.\n\n\u200b\n\nGetting a sense of how these efforts \"bite\" towards the end is vital to learning how to pace yourself over longer steady-state efforts; whether that's a time trial, local climb, breakaway, triathlon, or even a good old fitness test. In each of those cases, the pacing is key. Learning how your perceived effort can steadily climb even though your power remains unchanged is critical to good pacing.\n\n\u200b\n\nSo how do you know if you are doing this one right? As we said, the first 5 minutes should feel relatively easy. Around that 5-minute mark, your heart rate should stop climbing, and settle into 2-5% below your Lactate Threshold Heart Rate (LTHR). If your heart rate is climbing for the entire effort and goes above your LTHR, then you are going too hard.\n\nIf you hit the 10-minute mark, your legs feel fine, and your heart rate is still in Zone 3, then you aren't going hard enough.\n\nIf you've never done a session like this before, you can consider only doing the first 20-minute effort, or even sticking to just the first 15 minutes of each effort. There's no shame in building up to this full session, so don't be afraid to pause and fast forward as needed.\n\n\u200b\n\nNailing this session is really about getting in tune with your body and understanding what the edge between a sustainable and an unsustainable effort feels like. Not being able to complete this workout is fairly common, so don't beat yourself up if you can't make it through the first few times. As long as you come away from this session with a better understanding of how to pace longer efforts, you've improved as an athlete.\n",

Celebrated as a talented racer during his historic triple win in the Ardennes classics, the Italian fell after his positive test at the Beijing Olympics. His bronze medal would have a bitter aftertaste, that of the era of cycling in the \u201990s to which he belongs. Rebellin contests but returns his medal and serves a two-year suspension. In a sport that discards its black sheep and welcomes back others, Rebellin finds refuge in a modest Polish team upon his return and skims the minor races while former colleagues Basso, Scarponi, and Di Luca came back to the top level of the sport unscathed.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe years go by and on the road to redemption, the Venetian ends up stranded on the other side of the Mediterranean. An Algerian team takes him in without a contract. With neither air-conditioned bus nor energy bars, Rebellin stocks up on dates from the hills of Oran and turns his legs, sometimes 6 to 7 hours in a single day. In the peloton, while rubbing against riders half his age, Rebellin never forgets to remove his glasses at key moments of the race to gain clarity, as in 2004, in the wall of Huy. A resolute morning gaze of this touching fragility which earned him, in his early days, a nickname: \u201cIl Chierichetto\u201d (\u201cthe choirboy\u201d). Wrinkles have now carved out furrows on his face and his style is now less explosive. Davide has aged. He is 47 years old at the time of filming.             "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/a63aa70b-934b-47bf-acc0-5054c2afd5f9-running_noVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "Please write this running workout down and follow it. It cannot be completed in the app or shared to devices yet.",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "This is a technique-focused session designed to develop your agility, stability, range of motion, and foot speed. There is no focus on heart rate zones so you may choose to leave your monitor at home for these sessions. Between sets of each drill, you should jog/walk easily to fully recover between the efforts. While these efforts shouldn\u2019t be too taxing on you, the key is perfect form, so you want to be hitting each one rested enough that you can maintain great form for the duration. You should take a bit of extra rest between techniques, again to ensure you are rested and can nail the form. Before starting the workout, familiarize yourself with the format for high knees, butt kicks, skipping, carioca and strides. Find a flat track, field, or 50-100m of open space to perform this workout (football and soccer fields are great for this).\n\n\u200b\n\nFor help understanding your run workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/RunningSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-up:**\n\nStart off with 5-10 minutes of easy jogging/walking.\n\nHigh Knees: 2-3 sets of 50m high knees.\n\nEasy jog/walk for 30-60 seconds between.\n\n- Take short strides, bringing your knees up high enough that your upper legs are parallel to the ground. Focus on achieving high knees AND quick turnover, or performing as many reps as possible in a short distance.\n\n**Butt Kicks:**\n\n2-3 sets of 50m butt kicks.\n\nEasy jog/walk for 30-60 seconds between.\n\n- This should actually look similar to a high knee drill, but with the heels coming up to touch the bottom of your butt. Take short strides while using your hamstrings to lift your heels up beneath your butt. Your knees should come up in front of your body while pulling your heels up beneath your hips, rather than keeping your quads and knees below and in line with your hips.\n\n**Skipping:**\n\n3-4 sets of 50m skipping.\n\nEasy jog/walk for 30-60 seconds between.\n\n- Focus on a high knee drive and swinging your arms at your sides like you would when running.\n\n**Carioca:**\n\n4 sets of 30m Carioca in each direction (8 total).\n\nRest for 20 seconds between direction changes (at your discretion).\n\n- For this drill, you need to face sidewise to the direction you want to go. Start off moving to the right. Bring your left knee up and across your body and put your left foot in front of your right foot. Step your right foot to the right so it is parallel with your left leg again (at this point you should be positioned in the same direction and orientation that you were at the start. Next step your left leg behind your right leg, again so it lands on the right side of your right leg. Then bring your right leg back across your body, once again ending up in the starting position. Repeat this pattern for 25-30m.\n\n**Strides:**\n\n2-3 sets of 60m; Gradually build effort from RPE 3-8.\n\nEasy jog/walk for 30-60 seconds between. These are comprised of a steady acceleration over 60-80m up to 5k pace. The goal is to increase speed after each step, so you are reaching maximum speed at the end of the 60-80m stretch. You want to focus on keeping your shoulders, neck, and jaw relaxed while maintaining strong knee drive, straight and compact arm swing, planting the feet beneath the hips, and fast turnover.\n\n\u200b\n\nHigh Knees + Butt Kicks: \n\nFinish these drills with one set each of 50m high knees and butt kicks.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool-down:**\n\nWalk or jog for 5 minutes to cool down.\n\nIn case you need to brush up on your running [drills](https://wahoosystm.com/RunningSessionFAQ)\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "Please write this swimming workout down and follow it poolside. It cannot be completed in the app or shared to devices yet.",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "In case you need to brush up on your other [technique definitions or drills](https://wahoosystm.com/HelpCenterSwimDrills).\n\nFor help understanding your swim workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/SwimSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\nGood swimming technique is the key to efficient swimming. Today's session is a low intensity workout that challenges you with a series of drills designed to reinforce proper technique that will make you a more efficient, powerful and faster swimmer.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n200m stroke of your choice @ RPE 2 -- Z1\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 1**\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nInterval Distance: 25m Drill of choice\n\nThe goal of a Drill set is not to swim at any given pace, but instead focus on proper form. Choose a drill or focus on one of these key points for each 25m interval:\n\n- \\*Body position- swim on horizontal plane\n- \\*Enter in front of shoulder- preventing cross over\n- \\*Breathe early- prevent wide stroke- elbow is always widest point\n- \\*Elbow is always the highest point of the stroke\n- \\*Back of hand always faces direction of travel\n- \\*Fingers to point at the bottom of pool\n- \\*Initiate your stroke from the hips\n\nRecovery: 10 seconds rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 2**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nInterval Distance:\n\n200m Pull @ RPE 3-4 -- Z2\n\n- This set eliminates the use of your legs. It requires a buoy that you can swim with between your legs. The buoy will keep your body in the correct orientation. By removing your legs from the drill you will be required to only use your arms. This will help you focus on efficient form and making the most of each stroke!\n\nRecovery: 20 seconds rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nThe following should all be done at a moderate pace (RPE 2-4 -- Z1-Z2), with enough rest between that you can focus on proper form\n\nInterval 1: 150m of One Arm Freestyle drill\n\n- This is an old standby. Put your non-pulling arm out in front of your body and swim with only the opposite arm. Take some time to watch the arm that is pulling. Feel your elbow directly above your hand and that you are pulling right down the midline of your body. Split your body in half with your fingertips. Your emphasis should be on power and efficiency not on speed.\n- See how few strokes you can take to get down the pool.\n- Once you have it mastered, you can leave the non-pulling arm at your side.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 2: 200m of 3/4 Catch Up drill\n\n- A variation to catch-up that takes us closer to the full stroke. Another way to describe this is almost catch-up. Take a stroke with the right hand, wait until this hand is almost all the way through recovery and then start your pull with the left. This creates a very rhythmic feel, almost like skating through the water. Take your pull and ride the glide from it. When you lose speed, take your next pull. Want a good example of this? Watch Olympic replays of the Aussies, particularly Ian Thorpe. He races like this drill. Efficiency is your goal.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 3: 200m of Elbow-Hip-Elbow drill\n\n- A variation on side glide kick. The same goals apply balance, body roll, and head position during breathing. Start on either side with one arm extended out front, and the other at your side. With the fingers of the hand at your side, touch the elbow of your upper arm, then your hip, and then the elbow again. Now take your stroke or three strokes. Kick and glide and repeat.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 4: 150m of Fist Drill\n\n- Swim freestyle with your hands in fists. This is going to force you to get your forearms involved in the stroke because they have more surface area than your hands. Keep your elbow high under the water. Your forearm, from elbow to fingertips should be perpendicular to the bottom of the pool. Again, watch Ian Thorpe. You will feel like you are slipping through the water which is normal, however, the more water you feel like you are pulling the more efficient you are getting.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 5: 200m of Zipper Drill\n\n- This drill is done by pulling the fingers up the side of the body until they come into the armpit. The point of this is to keep a nice high elbow on recovery and to force the body to roll. Many use the Fingertip drag drill to accomplish this but we prefer this drill because the body roll essentially gives this drill a dual purpose.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nRepeat until full swim time is completed\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n200m stroke of your choice @ RPE < 2 -- Z1\n\n\u200b\n\n**Total Distance**\n\n1600m\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

                    "body": "In case you need to brush up on your swimming [technique definitions or drills](https://wahoosystm.com/HelpCenterSwimDrills).\n\nFor help understanding your swim workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/SwimSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\nGood swimming technique is the key to efficient swimming. Today's session is a low intensity workout that challenges you with a series of drills designed to reinforce proper technique that will make you a more efficient, powerful and faster swimmer.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n200m stroke of your choice @ RPE 2 -- Z1\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 1**\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nInterval Distance: 25m Drill of your choice\n\nThe goal of a Drill set is not to swim at any given pace, but instead focus on proper form. Choose a drill or focus on one of these key points for each 25m interval:\n\n- \\*Body position- swim on horizontal plane\n- \\*Enter in front of shoulder- preventing cross over\n- \\*Breathe early- prevent wide stroke- elbow is always widest point\n- \\*Elbow is always the highest point of the stroke\n- \\*Back of hand always faces direction of travel\n- \\*Fingers to point at the bottom of pool\n- \\*Initiate your stroke from the hips\n\nRecovery: 10-sec rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 2**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nInterval Distance: 100m kick @ RPE 3-4 -- Z2\n\n- This drill requires you to only use your legs for propulsion. Face the sky with your arms extended above your head, biceps squeezing your ears. Kick from the hips with straight legs, toes just breaking the surface of the water. When you see the flags above your head, flip onto your belly so you don't hit the wall. Make note if there are no flags at your pool before doing this drill so you can look for another sign that the wall is near.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 3**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nInterval Distance: 100m Pull @ RPE 3-4 -- Z2\n\n- This set eliminates the use of your legs to focus on your catch and pull. Squeeze a pull buoy between your legs to keep your hips afloat and body in the correct orientation.\n- While the back of the hand always faces the direction of travel and the elbow remains the highest point of the stroke, your leading hand spears the water and the Catch phase is initiated by obtaining a grasp on the water while reaching forward. This first phase is not about producing power, rather, it sets you up for the Pull and Push Phases. Imagine pulling yourself over a barrel. Hold as much water as possible while pulling, then pushing the water back to your thigh keeping the hand on the inside on the elbow. Your stroke should accelerate as you progress through the Pull and Push Phases. There is a subtle S formation that occurs during the phases, starting with the Pull Phase just above the shoulder and continuing through the Push Phase until your hand exits the water to begin the recovery phase. Always imagine a line dividing your body lengthwise, with your left arm staying on the left side and your right arm staying on the right side. Crossover will result in additional drag and unwanted sway in the lower body.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Set**\n\nComplete at least six of the drills that you struggle the most with. Aim for 150-200m of each one. The only way to get better is to work on your weaknesses! So be honest with yourself and pick the drills you have the hardest time with.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n200m stroke of your choice @ RPE < 2 -- Z1\n\n\u200b\n\n**Total Distance**\n\n2000m\n",

                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness.  While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are just times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs. \n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing.  Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high, your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week, but only if you do it right!\n\n\u200b\n\nMost people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\" Truth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted. So what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like?\n\nFor 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70% is ok, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in mid to low Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR, up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can, for most this is 80-90rpm and your RPE should be a 2-4 on a scale of 1-10.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right?  It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster.  You will have to trust us on that one!  When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions!  Or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70% \n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets\n\n8.5\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set\n\n1\n\nInterval:\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "The goal of this session is to accumulate a significant amount of time near your VO2max, or the point at which your body is consuming as much oxygen as it possibly can. That means your heart rate and breathing rate will both be near their max by the end of each interval, especially in the final few intervals.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince it takes time for your heart rate and breathing rate to match your effort, for the first part of each interval, you will be tapping into your Anaerobic Capacity to produce the required power. To account for this, we have limited the recovery duration to be equal to the interval duration. Limited recovery ensures that you will drain your Anaerobic Capacity before the end of the intervals, meaning your body will be forced to produce as much power as possible using oxygen.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <65%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n2 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n3 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: 3\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort: 2 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 95-105% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\nRecovery: 6 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 1 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Most people who have read or talked about High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT) have probably heard the term \"Tabata\" being thrown around, and for good reason. In the mid-'90s Professor Izumi Tabata set out to study the training impact of HIIT compared to a more traditional lower intensity high volume training. While both groups saw a similar increase in VO2max, only the HIIT group improved their Anaerobic Capacity, which is often associated with an increased ability to repeat hard efforts.\n\n\u200b\n\nThe HIIT protocol that Professor Izumi Tabata used was 4-minute blocks broken into what we refer to as \"Micro-Intervals\" 20sec efforts well above VO2max power (similar to what we refer to as MAP) and 10 seconds of recovery.\nThis was one of the first widely recognized studies that promoted HIIT, and since HIIT is The Sufferfest's Specialty, we would be crazy not to include this session.\n\n\u200b\n\nDuring this session, you are looking at 3 sets of Micro-Intervals in 4-minute blocks, with each 20sec power target exceeding 100% of your MAP. While the targets we have set are slightly lower than Tabata's original study, those subjects only completed one 4-minute block of their high-intensity session, and you get to complete 3 of them! That means if you finish the first set feeling fine, increase MAP intensity by 5%, or just switch to slope mode and get back to using RPE; these are MAX intervals after all, so just give it what you've got!\n\n\nThis session really does pack a punch, and being mentally prepared for it is more important than being physically prepared. By design, this session will completely drain your AC and max out your aerobic system. No one gets to that point and feels \"good.\" You need to mentally brace yourself to get into the hurt locker and stay down there until the bitter end.\n\n\u200b\n\nUncertain if you have that mental toughness or skill set to handle this session? Then check out the \"Getting Positive\" module on our Mental Toughness Program. While we encourage everyone to try MTP from start to finish (which takes about 10 weeks) just doing this one module can be incredibly beneficial.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minute @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP)\n\n2.5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Efforts**\n\nNumber of Sets: 3\n\nRest Between Sets: 6 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 8\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort: 20 seconds @ RPE 10 -- MAX EFFORT\n\nRecovery: 10 seconds @ RPE 1 -- <45% of FTP\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n6 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

Limited recovery ensures that you will drain your Anaerobic Capacity before the end of the intervals, meaning your body will be forced to produce as much power as possible using oxygen.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- 90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 2\n\nRest Between Sets: 2 hours @ RPE 4 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 8\n\n**Interval **\n\nEffort: 1 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 90-110% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\nRecovery: 1 minutes @ RPE 2 -- <45% of FTP\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "Standing starts closely simulates a lifting session on the bike because it requires the engagement of your core, upper, and lower body. It trains your ability to generate force through the pedals by ensuring you recruit ALL of your muscles to get that crank turning. No matter your preferred discipline, these efforts are key to teaching your body to recruit all of the muscle fibers in your legs. The saying \u201cUse it or Lose it\u201d actually does apply here.\n\n\u200b\n\nAll of the benefits in this session come from hitting these 20-second efforts as hard as you possibly can. To do that, you need full recovery between each sprint, and you need to respect that recovery! These efforts should see you start at super low RPMs with very high torque. As you start and increase the effort, your cadence will naturally increase. Your goal is to get your cadence as high as possible by the end of each 20-second effort. To maximize your muscle recruitment, you want to both push down and pull up on the pedals at the start. Proper core engagement is a must - your legs need a good strong backboard to push against.\n\n\u200b\n\nWe understand that not everyone's trainer has the necessary resistance or the required stability to perform this workout as described. If you can't safely stand up, then you can get much of the same benefit by doing these efforts seated. If your trainer can\u2019t handle the rapid change in speed or does not have high enough resistance at a super low cadence, then you can start the efforts at a higher cadence and treat them as \u201cnormal\u201d all-out sprints.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR < 80%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 6\n\n**Interval **\n\nStanding Start: 20 seconds @ RPE 10 --\n\nStarting from standing (or very very very slow rolling) starts in a 53x14 gear.                     "body": "This is a session that you'll want to complete in Level, rather than Erg, mode. The only time we would suggest Erg mode is if you are unable to maintain the lower power targets set between sprints.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith short maximal sprint efforts, you'll recruit every muscle fiber you have in your legs each effort. While cadence builds force your muscles to contract and relax as quickly as possible, this session forces your muscles to contract with maximal force. Just like cadence builds this session becomes one of the best ways to train your neuromuscular system. Even if your target event does not require you to complete maximal sprints, there is a substantial trickle-down effect to the longer duration power efforts when you train your neuromuscular system.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session is a great alternate to cadence builds or standing starts for those completing our SUF Strength sessions. On days you completely off the bike strength work you want your on-bike training to complement the suffering you put yourself through off the bike. That means short maximal efforts (whether for power or for cadence) are the best workouts to complement the strength gains you've made off the bike.\n\n\u200b\n\nAs long as you run this session in slope mode you can complete the sprints either seated or out of the saddle. For those competing in events that do not require much (if any) standing (such as Time Trials or Triathlons) you should complete these sprints seated (and in the aero bars or drops if that is where you are racing).\n\nYou should also do these efforts seated if you don't feel an out-of-the-saddle maximal sprint is stable/safe to do on your trainer. Regardless of using ERG or Slope mode, you do not want to hold anything back on any sprint. Seeing your peak power drop as the session goes on is totally normal as your legs fatigue. This is where RPE really becomes the most important metric, rather than power, heart rate, or cadence. Now get on that bike and CRUSH IT!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 12\n\n**Interval **\n\nSprint: 10 seconds @ RPE 10 -- MAX SPRINT\n\nRecovery: 5 minutes 50 seconds @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Technique & Drills",
            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/91fd8529-8bf4-40e9-a1ce-e7131e5fea1c-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. The ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT is planned for a future release.",
                            "severity": "Information"
                        },
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "If your trainer doesn't have the resistance or stability to perform this workout as described, don't worry. For stability issues, you can do these efforts seated. If your trainer can\u2019t handle the rapid change in speed or does not have high enough resistance at low cadence then you can start the efforts at a higher cadence and simply treat them as normal all-out sprints.",
                            "severity": "Error"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "In this session, you will be going straight from a max 20-second high torque starting effort into 40 seconds right at your Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP). The starting effort should just about completely drain your Anaerobic Capacity (AC), which will leave you gasping for air as you start each 40-second MAP effort. By forcing yourself to maintain MAP after a maximal sprint, you are asking your body to increase oxygen supply to your muscles as quickly as possible by increasing your heart rate and breathing rate. Being able to increase oxygen consumption rapidly means your body will better handle changes in pace both above and below threshold.\n\n**What you need to do:**\n\n- You'll need to begin each Standing Start at super low RPMs with very high torque (high resistance). To maximize muscle recruitment you want to both push-down and pull-up on the pedals at the start. Proper core engagement is a must, as your legs need a sturdy backboard to push against.\n- You'll want the starting resistance to be just high enough that only your max effort can get the pedals moving; after those first few revs, your goal is to get your cadence up as high as possible by the end of the 20 seconds.\n- For smart trainer users, the best way to ensure you have the right resistance is to complete this session in Level Mode rather than ERG Mode.\n- Once the 20-second start is over you want to settle right into the 40-second effort at MAP, avoiding any significant drop in power at the transition point. Since the goal of this 40-second MAP effort is maximal cardiovascular demand, aim to hold your cadence 10-15 RPM higher than you would for the 5-minute test in Full Frontal.\n\n**For Time Trialists and Triathletes:**\n\nAfter the Standing Start, you will want to get into your aero bars and hold the same position you will be competing in. Those on regular road bikes should get down into the drops.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n2 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR < 80%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 5\n\n**Interval **\n\nStanding Start: 20 seconds @ RPE 10 --\n\nStarting from standing (or very very very slow rolling) starts in a 53x14 gear.                     "body": "While some of you will know this intensity level as \"Sweet-Spot\", we prefer the name Sub-Threshold, because we want to drive home the fact that you should keep your power below FTP. In the same way that longer Tempo efforts can feel \"easy,\" these shorter Sub-Threshold efforts can also feel \"easy\". After all, if you can hold 100% of FTP for about an hour, then holding less than that for 5-minutes should be a piece of cake right? We know you can go harder for 5-minutes, but that is not what we are asking for.\n\n\nThis session is not intended to push you to your limits, nor is it designed to be a massive training load. The real purpose is to essentially keep your fatigue levels right where they are, by giving your body just enough intensity to ensure that you are not \"more recovered\" after today.\n\n\nWhile some folks will say that there is no training benefit to such short Sub-Threshold efforts, when viewed in a bigger picture sense (like a 3-week training block) they can be the perfect efforts to ensure you get the most out of a longer training block.\n\n\nWe would even ask that you view this session as more of an assessment, rather than strictly a workout. That's because you should be comparing this power output to heart rate response and your own internal RPE. When you have heavy fatigue, your heart rate will struggle to hit its normal peaks. When fresh you would be getting into Z4 heart rate by the end of the last two intervals, and your RPE should never really climb above a 7. When holding onto excess fatigue, your heart rate won't climb above Z3, and your RPE will be above an 8. At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.\n\n\nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 4\n\n**Interval **\n\nSurge: 30 sec @ RPE 8.5 -- 90% of MAP (105-130% of FTP)\n\nSteady: 2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n9 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
