                    "body": "The training benefit of this session comes down to the uncomfortably high cadence you need to hold during each effort. Even though these efforts are under FTP, the high leg speed required will leave your system working harder than usual for the required power output.\n\n\nBy maintaining the highest cadence possible (without bouncing in the saddle) you end up pushing your neuromuscular coordination near its limits in a similar way to Cadence Builds.\n\n\u200b\n\nWith an emphasis on low torque (high RPM) efforts, this session is the polar opposite to sessions like GOAT and Power Station. Even though these efforts are short and below FTP the high cadence places more of a load on your cardiovascular system, so expect your heart rate and breathing to be higher than normal for the power.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince muscles can only contract (pull) any given muscle will primarily move a joint in a single direction. When it comes to pedaling a bike, your quads and glutes can push the pedals down, while your hamstrings and hip flexors pull the pedals back up (with the help of your glutes and quads on the other leg). If you were to pedal with one leg (as you do in Cadence Drills) and your hamstrings and glutes were unable to contract, once you get to the bottom of the pedal stroke your leg would be stuck down there. No matter how hard you might try, your glutes and quads will do nothing to help you get that pedal all the way around. Suppose you do have both feet clipped in, and you are letting your opposite leg push down to bring your leg back up to 12 o'clock. If your quads and glutes are still contracting (pushing the pedal down) while the glutes and quads of your other leg are starting to push their pedal down, you will end up with one leg working against the other. You must relax the glutes and quads of one leg to get all of the power out of the glutes and quads of your other leg.\n\nThis is where neuromuscular coordination comes into play. During each pedal revolution, your legs have to \u201cswitch on\u201d and \u201cswitch off\u201d almost all of the muscles in your legs. By maintaining your highest cadence without bouncing, you are pushing all of the muscles in each leg to contract and relax (switch on and off) as quickly as possible.\n\n\nWhile we give specific cadence targets in this session, everyone has a different limit to what cadence they can maintain before bouncing in the saddle. To get the intended benefit of this session you need to maintain the power targets at the highest cadence that YOU can maintain. For some that might be 105RPM, for others, it might be 150RPM. What matters is that you push YOUR neuromuscular system to its limits.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 5\n\n**Interval **\n\nEffort: 5 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 80% of FTP -- 100+ RPM -- HR <95%\n\nRecovery: 8 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n18 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "While the single tempo effort you complete in this session is steady in terms of power, it is the specific cadence targets that set this session apart from other tempo workouts.\n\n\u200b\n\nEven though an effort at 80% of FTP might seem \"easy\" the truth is your body is working at processing oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate when you are right at FTP. The difference is that the overall stress on your system when riding tempo is considerably less than riding at FTP. That means you can either have harder days before or after a tempo session (compared to a Threshold session) or you can increase the duration of those tempo efforts to make the overall training stimulus equal (or greater) than completing several repeats right at your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis tempo effort is divided into 3 segments of equal duration. While the power is the same across all segments, your target cadence starts and low and increases with each new segment. Starting with a long block of low cadence should fatigue your muscles from the start of your effort. As the effort builds and you create more fatigue, the increased cadence targets will place a greater demand on your cardiovascular system. That will, in some way, feel like a nice break given the load you have been putting on your muscular system. The cadence targets in the final segment will force your fatigued muscles to maintain good coordination as the faster cadence requires your muscles to switch \"on\" and \"off\" at a faster rate. Between the low rpm sections, and the high rpm work under fatigue, this tempo session not only helps train your FTP, but it has a training benefit to your neuromuscular system.\n\n\u200b\n\nYou can expect your Heart Rate to remain low for the power targets during the low cadence segment at the start. As the effort progresses and you reach the final 10 minutes of the high rpm segment your heart rate might go over Z3, which is not something to worry about. While this session appears \"easy\" at first glance, don't be surprised if your legs are feeling it the next day.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 110% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 1\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort 1: 15 minutes @ RPE 5.5 -- 80% of FTP-- 55-65 RPM -- HR <85%\n\nEffort 2: 15 minutes @ RPE 5.5 -- 80% of FTP-- 70-80 RPM -- HR <90%\n\nEffort 3: 15 minutes @ RPE 5.5 -- 80% of FTP-- 90+ RPM -- HR <95%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n25 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR < 70%\n",

                    "body": "Tempo sessions are always a great time to work on pace control. We are taking that pacing demand a bit further in this session by forcing you to slightly increase your effort as time goes on. This is referred to as a \"Negative-Split\", meaning the second half is faster (or you hold a higher power) than the first half.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhile you might question the benefit of doing \"easier\" tempo efforts, the truth is when riding between 80% and 100% of FTP your body processes oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate. Holding a higher power will give you a higher single day training stimulus, but looking at the big picture that can have its drawbacks. Mainly the fatigue those harder sessions cause, which requires easier workouts the days before and after. Sticking to the Tempo targets gets you nearly the same training stimulus while allowing you to hit harder sessions the rest of the week.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session contains a single 30-minute tempo effort, broken into three 10-minute segments. You will spend the first 10-minutes at 80% of FTP, the next 10 at 84%, and the final 10 at 87%. By the time you hit the last 10-minutes of this effort, that 87% will feel much harder than it should. Another way of thinking about this one, if you were to reverse the order, and start at 87%, what you would likely find is that your RPE stays fairly consistent for the entire effort, even though the power targets are dropping.\n\n\u200b\n\nOverheating, not drinking enough, being under-fueled and mental fatigue will all play a factor in how you feel in that final block. They will also impact your heart rate. While these power targets are usually associated with Zone 3 heart rate, many people will see their heart rate climb into low Z4 if they are not hydrating properly, or have inadequate cooling. This can be a great session to act as a \"wake up call\" on any poor training habits you might have, so take note and aim to address those issues during your next workout.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 110% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 1\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort 1: 10 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 80% of FTP-- HR <85%\n\nEffort 2: 10 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 83% of FTP-- HR <90%\n\nEffort 3: 10 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 87% of FTP-- HR <95%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n1 hour 15 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR < 70%\n",

                    "body": "When it comes to \"peaking\", or performing at your absolute best on a given day, the key is nailing your Taper.\nThe term \"Taper\" refers to the time leading up to your target date, where your total volume of training is reduced, but you continue to hit several high-intensity efforts.\n\n\nWhile there are individual variations in what makes the ideal taper for you, this session has been used by countless professionals leading into the biggest races of their lives. Riders who use this session leading up to an event include world champions Rohan Dennis and Flora Duffy.\n\n\nWith 3 sets of micro-intervals (40/20s, 30/30s, and 20/40s) you will be hitting your system with just enough intensity to keep your legs sharp and responsive, without adding any real fatigue to your system.\n\n\nOutside of those 3 sets of micro-intervals, this session is purposefully short and easy. If you are doing this session your event is just around the corner, and all of the important training is behind you. Riding harder or longer today will do absolutely nothing to increase your fitness by event day; in fact, all that would do is increase your fatigue, which will only hurt your performance.\n\n\nThis is a preparation session, not a training session!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <65%\n\n1 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-190% of FTP)\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Efforts **\n\nNumber of Sets: 3, all unique\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n**Set 1 **\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 6\n\nInterval: Effort: 40 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 95% of MAP (110-135% of FTP)\n\nRecovery: 20 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n**Set 2 **\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 5\n\nEffort: 30 seconds @ RPE 9.5 -- 110-130% of MAP (125-170% of FTP)\n\nRecovery: 30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n**Set 3 **\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 4\n\nEffort: 20 seconds @ RPE 10 -- 100% of AC (140-220% of FTP)\n\nRecovery: 40 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "Just like Fight Club and Who Dares, this session is all about surging well above threshold, and then trying to recover without dropping your power anywhere close to your recovery zone. The 2 things that make this session stand out are:\n\n1. You only have one single continuous effort (which happens to be 45-minutes in length)\n2. Your recovery power is low Tempo, which is good because any higher than that and you wouldn't last the full 60 minutes!\n\nAs you increase the intensity from 80% of FTP up to 100% of FTP, your legs begin to produce more and more metabolites, but the rate at which your body CAN clear them is almost the same. As you close in on 100% of FTP you suddenly are at a point where the production of metabolites equals your clearance rate. Now move just a bit over FTP and those metabolites are going to continue to build until you drop your effort back below FTP.\n\n\nTo improve your body's clearance rate for those metabolites, you need to spend a decent amount of time with more of those metabolites in your system than your body's current clearance rate can handle.\n\n\nThat is what this session is all about, short hard efforts above FTP to build an excess of metabolites, followed by steady riding at 80% of FTP. This steady-state effort between surges is high enough that your body will still be working at max clearance rates but low enough that you can keep doing those surges over and over again, which is good for you because this is not a short interval.\n\n\nWhile you can achieve the same training stimuli by holding shorter blocks above FTP, those sessions have their drawbacks. The main one is nailing the exact right intensity above FTP that will allow you to accumulate enough time in that metabolite flooded state. While we like to think our FTP is set in stone, the reality is it can fluctuate from day to day, which makes finding that balancing point for a session like that so difficult. You can easily go too hard and blow up early, or not go hard enough and never really push that clearance rate to the max. By hitting surges well above FTP, then holding an effort a good deal below FTP, any day to day variation in your FTP becomes less of an issue because you never have to dance 5W above or below it.\n\n\nThe added benefit to this Surge and Settle workout style is the boost it can give to your Anaerobic Capacity. An improved AC means you can recover faster, not just from sprint type efforts, but from repeated MAP and FTP efforts as well.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 110% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 9\n\n**Interval **\n\nSurge: 20 seconds @ RPE 8 -- 110% of FTP\n\nSteady: 4min 40sec @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n1 hour 15 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

The difference is that the overall stress on your system when riding tempo is considerably less than riding at FTP. That means you can either have harder days before or after a tempo session (compared to a Threshold session) or you can increase the duration of those tempo efforts to make the overall training stimulus equal (or greater) than completing several repeats right at your FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n25 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 5\n\n**Interval **\n\nEffort: 2 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- 45-55 RPM -- HR <95%\n\nRecovery: 5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n35 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "While some of you will know this intensity level as \"Sweet-Spot\", we prefer the name Sub-Threshold, because we want to drive home the fact that you should keep your power below FTP. In the same way that longer Tempo efforts can feel \"easy,\" these shorter Sub-Threshold efforts can also feel \"easy\". After all, if you can hold 100% of FTP for about an hour, then holding less than that for 5-minutes should be a piece of cake right? We know you can go harder for 5-minutes, but that is not what we are asking for.  \nThis session is not intended to push you to your limits, nor is it designed to be a massive training load. The real purpose is to essentially keep your fatigue levels right where they are, by giving your body just enough intensity to ensure that you are not \"more recovered\" after today.  \nWhile some folks will say that there is no training benefit to such short Sub-Threshold efforts, when viewed in a bigger picture sense (like a 3-week training block) they can be the perfect efforts to ensure you get the most out of a longer training block.  \nWe would even ask that you view this session as more of an assessment, rather than strictly a workout. That's because you should be comparing this power output to heart rate response and your own internal RPE. When you have heavy fatigue, your heart rate will struggle to hit its normal peaks. When fresh you would be getting into Z4 heart rate by the end of the last two intervals, and your RPE should never really climb above a 7. When holding onto excess fatigue, your heart rate won't climb above Z3, and your RPE will be above an 8. At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.  \nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.  \n  \n**Warm-Up **15 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%  \n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%  \n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%  \n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR < 90%  \n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <95%  \n30 seconds @ RPE 8 -- 115% of FTP  \n6 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <80%  \n  \n**Main Effort **Number of Sets: 3  \nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%  \nInterval Repeats per Set: 1  \n**Interval **Surge: 20 seconds @ RPE 9.5 -- 90% of AC (135-190%+ of FTP)  \nSteady: 15 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%  \n  \n**Extra Volume **NA  \n  \n**Cool Down **4 minutes @ RPE 1 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%  \n",

Extend the left arm out in front of shoulder, grab hold of the imaginary rope between your thumb and forefinger, then pretend you are swimming over a barrel extending the arm down your side, before returning your arm to front by creeping it underwater up the side of your body. Arms should be in opposite positions. Head should be in the water which will allow for a greater forward rotation of the shoulder when initiating the stroke!             "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/36886c84-ecfa-4620-9e71-d2c78fdb1417-swimming_noVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "Please write this swimming workout down and follow it poolside. It cannot be completed in the app or shared to devices yet.",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Good swimming technique is the key to efficient swimming. Today's session is a low intensity workout that challenges you with a series of drills designed to reinforce proper technique that will make you a more efficient, powerful and faster swimmer.\n\n\u200b\n\nIn case you need to brush up on your other swimming [technique definitions or drills](https://wahoosystm.com/HelpCenterSwimDrills).\n\nFor help understanding your swim workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/SwimSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n200m stroke of your choice @ RPE 2 -- Z1\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 1**\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nInterval Distance: 25m Drill of your choice\n\nThe goal of a Drill set is not to swim at any given pace, but instead focus on proper form. Choose a drill or focus on one of these key points for each 25m interval:\n\n- Body position- swim on horizontal plane\n- Enter in front of shoulder- preventing cross over\n- Breathe early- prevent wide stroke- elbow is always widest point\n- Elbow is always the highest point of the stroke\n- Back of hand always faces direction of travel\n- Fingers to point at the bottom of pool\n- Initiate your stroke from the hips\n\nRecovery: 10 sec rest\n\n**Activation 2**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nInterval Distance: 200m Kick @ RPE 5 -- Z3\n\n- This drill requires you to only use your legs for propulsion. Face the sky with your arms extended above your head, biceps squeezing your ears. Kick from the hips with straight legs, toes just breaking the surface of the water. When you see the flags above your head, flip onto your belly so you don't hit the wall. Make note if there are no flags at your pool before doing this drill so you can look for another sign that the wall is near.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nThe following should all be done at a moderate pace (RPE 2-4 -- Z1-Z2), with enough rest between that you can focus on proper form\n\nInterval 1: 100m of Super Slow Drill\n\n- This should be done for 25m at a time. Slow down your stroke rate as much as possible. In fact, the point here is to see how slowly you can go without sinking. Work hard to swim with perfect form concentrating not on how much water you are pulling but rather what position your hands, body, and feet are in. This drill will help you keep your balance in the water. If you can balance going slow, you can balance going fast.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 2: 100m swim, incorporating the\n\nInterval 3: 150m of 3-3-3 Drill\n\n- Simply put, take three strokes with your left, three with your right, and three whole strokes (6 arm pulls). This is good for a couple of things: First, continue to work on the efficiency of the one-arm strokes. Secondly, When you switch sides, you want to work on the transfer of power from right to left. Then when you take full strokes, you can quickly get into long, efficient strokes.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 3: 200m of Catch Up Drill\n\n- Another old standby. Swim freestyle one arm at a time. Take a stroke with the right and touch your left arm that is out in front of the body. Then take your pull with the left hand. Be sure that you are not rushing. Get as much out of each arm stroke that you can. Remember, freestyle is not of stroke of constant propulsion. It is a pull with the left and then the right. It is important that we approach it this way.\n\nRecovery: 20 sec rest\n\nInterval 4: 200m of Side-Glide-Kick Drill\n\n- Push off the wall on your side and kick for eight kicks. Keep your ear on your arm and your body straight. Make sure your knees are passing one another when you kick. After eight kicks, take a good pull with the arm on top. Use this pull to roll you to the other side and repeat the cycle. For variation do this drill with three strokes in between. I.e. on the right side with the right arm up and the left arm at your side. Take a pull with the right, left, and then right. End with your left arm up and your right arm at your side. This will help your body position in the water and if you keep your head on your arm when you are on your side it will help your head position when you breathe.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 5: 200m of Corkscrew Swim\n\n- This is done by alternating one stroke of freestyle and one stroke of backstroke. This repetition makes you roll over and around from front to back repeatedly, thus \"corkscrewing.\u201d This is useful because most of us will want to cross our bodies when we roll from our back to our stomach. Fight this and try to take perfect midline strokes over and over.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nInterval 6: 200m Pull\n\n- This set eliminates the use of your legs to focus on your catch and pull. Squeeze a pull buoy between your legs to keep your hips afloat and body in the correct orientation.\n- While the back of the hand always faces the direction of travel and the elbow remains the highest point of the stroke, your leading hand spears the water and the Catch phase is initiated by obtaining a grasp on the water while reaching forward. This first phase is not about producing power, rather, it sets you up for the Pull and Push Phases. Imagine pulling yourself over a barrel. Hold as much water as possible while pulling, then pushing the water back to your thigh keeping the hand on the inside on the elbow. Your stroke should accelerate as you progress through the Pull and Push Phases. There is a subtle S formation that occurs during the phases, starting with the Pull Phase just above the shoulder and continuing through the Push Phase until your hand exits the water to begin the recovery phase. Always imagine a line dividing your body lengthwise, with your left arm staying on the left side and your right arm staying on the right side. Crossover will result in additional drag and unwanted sway in the lower body.\n\nRecovery: 20-sec rest\n\nRepeat until full swim time is completed as directed by your training plan\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n200m stroke of your choice @ RPE < 2 -- Z1\n\n\u200b\n\n**Total Distance**\n\n1750m\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "This brutal but straightforward workout is perfect for developing both FTP and MAP while teaching you a Negative Split pacing strategy. For this workout, you will complete a series of 4-minute efforts. The first 3-minutes are right at your FTP, which isn't so tough in itself, but the final 1-minute of each effort are set above 90% of MAP.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhen we talk about a \"negative split\" we mean completing the second half of an effort at a higher speed/power than the first half. By the time you hit the MAP portion of each interval, your heart rate and breathing rate will already be nice and high. This limits the AC demand of a standalone MAP effort, where you have a large lag time between producing the power requirement, and your body delivering the oxygen needed to hold that power. Usually, that lag time between oxygen demand and oxygen supply is covered by your AC. Paced correctly, your heart rate should essentially be increasing for the entire 4-minutes, as it will be settling into LTHR right as you up the power output.\n\n\u200b\n\nAs you complete each effort, holding 100% of FTP will feel harder and harder. This in itself is excellent mental practice for \"feeling\" how your RPE for the same power can drift up as fatigue sets in. Knowing what 100% of FTP feels like when your legs are nearly spent is a great reminder of why starting an effort too hard will bite you in the end.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis workout ends up delivering a fantastic aerobic workload as you complete 8-minutes of MAP work with minimal help from your AC, making this an excellent session for those who have a strong AC but weak MAP. You also rack up 24-minutes at 100% of FTP, which by itself would be a good training load. Add in these MAP efforts, and you multiply the training impact of those 24-minutes.\n\n\u200b\n\nRegardless of your chosen discipline or event, this is a session that will benefit everyone, both regarding learning good pacing and giving your aerobic system a big training boost.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 8 -- 90% of MAP (105-135% of FTP)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 2\n\nRest Between Sets: 15 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 4\n\n**Interval**\n\nFTP Effort: 3 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\nVO2 Effort: 1 minute @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of MAP (105-130% of FTP) \n\nRecovery: 5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70% \n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 1 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "In this workout, the shorter the interval duration, the higher the power target will be. Starting from 20 minutes of low Tempo, and finishing with 4-minutes of high-quality MAP work, proper pacing is crucial to success in this workout. While you could easily be above target power for the entire 20-minute effort, that would set you up to fail in the last two efforts. Be smart and pace yourself; you can always go harder in the final 5-minute effort if you want to!\n\n\nAt any intensity above Endurance pace, the longer you ride, the more fatigued you become. Completing the final 5-minute target when fresh would be unpleasant, hitting it after all of these other intervals makes it a near maximal effort. Proper hydration/cooling and nutrition are vital if you want to nail this workout.\n\n\nIf you are preparing for any longer ride/event where you will be required to keep on the gas from start to finish, this is the perfect session for you. Completing these efforts in this order not only gives a great physical training boost but also toughens you up mentally. Digging deep when fatigued is the key to good performance over longer distances, so expect to suffer in that final 5-minute effort; it will pay off both mentally and physically!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 4, all unique\n\nRest Between Sets: 12 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: N/A\n\n**Set 1** (20-minute Effort)\n\nSteady: 20 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 85% of FTP-- HR <95%\n\n**Set 2** x4(16-minute Effort) \n\nSteady: 3 minutes @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\nSurge: 1 minute @ RPE 7.75 -- 105% of FTP-- HR <105%\n\n**Set 3 **(8-minute Effort)\n\nSurge: 1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 90% of MAP (105-125% of FTP)\n\nSteady: 6 minutes @ RPE 7.25 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\nSurge: 1 minute @ RPE 9 -- 95% of MAP (110-135% of FTP)\n\n**Set 4 **(4-minute Effort)\n\nEffort 1: 1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 90% of MAP (105-125% of FTP)\n\nEffort 2: 1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP\n\nEffort 3: 1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 90% of MAP (105-125% of FTP)\n\nEffort 4: 1 minute @ RPE 9.5 -- 100+% of MAP (120-150% of FTP)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n55 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "Tempo efforts are not maximal, and often feel too \"easy\", leading many people to turn a tempo effort into a Sub-Threshold or even Supra-Threshold effort. That is not the point! If we wanted you to go harder, you would see a different workout in your Training Plan. We know you can go harder for 25-minutes, but that is not the point of a Tempo Session.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhat many people don't realize is that your body's ability to process oxygen and metabolites is nearly identical from 80%-100% of FTP. The main change across that intensity range is the rate at which those metabolites are being generated. While you would get a slightly greater training load from doing this session at higher power, you would be adding more fatigue to your system than we want. That extra fatigue means you either need to ease off your workouts in the days leading up or ease off your workouts on the days after. From a big picture point of view that's no good! This session gives a great steady-state aerobic training load while leaving you fresh enough that you can hit training hard the days before and after. That means your training load over the entire week is often higher when you maintain restraint and stick to those Tempo Targets.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 110% of FTP -- HR <105%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 3\n\n**Interval **\n\nEffort: 20 minutes @ RPE 5.5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\nRecovery: 15 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n2 hours @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "This skills session is designed to mimic a variety of challenging course conditions and scenarios you will encounter on race day. The skills practiced here are done below race pace so you can focus on proper execution. To properly complete this ride you will need to find a field with the following features and bring along some equipment:  \n  \nA set of stairs, ideally with enough area at the top to practice re-mounting your bike.  \nA flat, open area to practice Figure 8s. Use water bottles or cones to mark the corners.  \nA hill to practice off-camber riding.  \nBarriers about shin high, which can be made from PVC pipe or improvised using your imagination (and a few water bottles).  \n  \nHere\u2019s how to tackle this session:  \n  \nWarm-up for 10-15 minutes Z1/Z2 spinning, include 2 x 1 minute Z3 efforts to warm up.  \n  \nStairs. Complete 3-4 sets:  \nApproach the stairs at a decent speed (but don\u2019t go over a Z3 effort).  \nDismount and focus on the technique needed to maintain your momentum up the stairs. Experiment with both the timing of your dismount and how you hold your bike while running up the stairs. You may wish to sling it over your shoulder or pick it up by the top tube and handlebars.  \nAt the top remount as smoothly as possible while trying to maintain your forward momentum.  \n  \nFigure 8s. Complete 5-10 minutes:  \nFor more info on Figure 8s read \u201cTips for Figure 8s\u201d.  \nSet up two bottles or cones roughly 20m apart and practice your Figure 8s.  \nFocus on maintaining your speed, and try to avoid accelerating or surging out of the \u201cturns\u201d.  \nIf you\u2019re feeling frisky you can break up the Figure 8s with 50-75m Field Runs every couple minutes.  \n  \nBarriers. Complete 4-8 sets:  \nNext, set up some barriers (you can make a portable set from PVC pipe, or you can use some water bottles and your imagination).  \nHit your barrer section at a decent speed (again trying to avoid going over Z3).  \nPractice and perfect the timing of your dismount and remount. The key here is keeping your leg speed quick and nimble between the barriers!  \n  \nOff-Camber Riding. Complete 5-10 minutes:  \nRide to the top of the hill and then ride along the length of the crest. Try to hold a straight line while not gaining or losing elevation.  \nTurn around and ride it in the opposite direction.  \nAs your off-camber skills develop you can try riding faster and faster to see where your limit is, and sometimes that means going over it! Be safe, but remember that you won\u2019t know what you can and can\u2019t do until you try!  \n  \nFinish with 5-10 minutes of easy spinning to cool down.  \n  \n**Warm-Up  \n**8 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%  \n1 minutes @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <75%  \n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <75%  \n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR < 80%  \n4 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%  \n  \n**Main Effort  \n**Number of Sets: 4  \nRest Between Sets: 2 minutes  \nInterval Repeats per Set: 1  \n**Interval  \n**8 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70% focusing on assigned skill  \n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%  \n  \n**Extra Volume  \n**N/A  \n  \n**Cool Down  \n**5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%  \n",

The skills practiced here are done at race pace so you can focus on proper execution while under pressure. To properly complete this ride you will need to find a field with the following features and bring along some equipment:  \n  \n- A set of stairs, ideally with enough area at the top to practice re-mounting your bike.  \n- A flat, open area to practice Figure 8s. Use water bottles or cones to mark the corners.  \n- A hill to practice off-camber riding.  \n- Barriers about shin high, which can be made from PVC pipe or improvised using your imagination (and a few water bottles).  \n- BONUS: an area with sand or deep and loose dirt.  \n  \nHere\u2019s how to tackle this session:  \n  \nWarm-up for 10-15 minutes Z1/Z2 spinning, include two 3-5 second hard accelerations.  \n  \nHole Shot + Stairs. Complete 2 sets:  \nSimulate your race start by lining up 300-400m away from the stairs, in your starting gear and with one foot unclipped.  \nCountdown from 10 and you\u2019re OFF! Clip in and complete an all out 15 second effort.  \nWork on shifting up smoothly during the effort as you would in a race.  \nContinue the effort around Z3/Z4 effort for 60 seconds while riding towards the base of the stairs.  \nDismount and run up the stairs and remount at the top.  \nBetween the first and second set, do 50-100m of Field Running.  \n  \nBarriers. Complete 4-6 sets:  \nSet up some barriers (you can make a portable set from PVC pipe, or you can use some water bottles and your imagination).  \nStarting about 100m out from your barriers, speed towards the barriers at race pace.  \nThe challenge is to focus on the timing of your dismount and remount and to keep you leg speed high between the barriers in order to maintain the most momentum.  \n  \nFigure 8s. Complete 5-10 minutes:  \nFor more info on Figure 8s read \u201cTips for Figure 8s\u201d.  \nSet up 2 bottles about 30m apart and practice your Figure 8s.  \nTo simulate a race scenario, drive your first 3-4 pedal strokes super hard coming out of each \u201cturn\u201d.  \nAlternate seated efforts and standing efforts and experiment with your gearing to find the best fit for your desired cadence and power.  \n  \nSand Pit. Extend the left arm out in front of shoulder, grab hold of the imaginary rope between your thumb and forefinger, then pretend you are swimming over a barrel extending the arm down your side, before returning your arm to the front by creeping it underwater up the side of your body. Arms should be in opposite positions. Head above the water as this gives you the opportunity to see where your arms are! If you have the availability, use the blue or black line as a reference guide. Recovery: 15 sec rest\n\n**Activation 2**\n\nNumber of Sets: 6\n\nInterval: 50m as: 25m zipper drill, 25m free @ RPE 3 -- Z2\n\n- This drill is done by pulling the fingers up the side of the body until they come up into the armpit. The point of this is to keep a nice high elbow on recovery and to force the body to roll. Many use the Fingertip drag drill to accomplish this. We prefer this drill as it incorporates the body roll for more bang for your buck. Recovery: 15 sec rest\n\n**Main Set**\n\nNumber of Sets: 3\n\nInterval: 400m as: 100m pull + 100m swim @ RPE 5-6 -- Z3, Focus on maintaining your stroke counts from start to finish.\n\nRecovery: 1.5 min rest\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n200m @ RPE 2 -- Z1, choice of strokes\n\n\u200b\n\n**Total Distance**\n\n2300m\n",

To perform the drill: Begin by running into water and as you progress into deeper water, be sure you are lifting your knees before duck diving is required. Once the water has reached hip height, begin swimming. Complete 20 strokes. Focus on maintaining your technique throughout. Repeat 5 times.\n\n\u200b\n\nLake Shore Entry- Follow the steps above\n\n\u200b\n\nDock Entry- Check surroundings to be sure they are safe for diving. From a standing start with a slight bend to the knees and your toes gripping the dock, bend forward from the hips keeping your buttocks raised, place one hand on top of the other, then place your head between your arms so that your chin is on your chest. As you push with your legs propel your body forward with your finger tips entering the water first. Once in the water, swim 20 strokes and return. Focus on maintaining your technique throughout.                 {
                    "__typename": "Description",

                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Standing starts closely simulates a lifting session on the bike because it requires the engagement of your core, upper, and lower body. It trains your ability to generate force through the pedals by ensuring you recruit ALL of your muscles to get that crank turning. No matter your preferred discipline, these efforts are key to teaching your body to recruit all of the muscle fibers in your legs. The saying \u201cUse it or Lose it\u201d actually does apply here.\n\n\u200b\n\nAll of the benefits in this session come from hitting these 20-second efforts as hard as you possibly can. To do that, you need full recovery between each sprint, and you need to respect that recovery! These efforts should see you start at super low RPMs with very high torque. As you start and increase the effort, your cadence will naturally increase. Your goal is to get your cadence as high as possible by the end of each 20-second effort. To maximize your muscle recruitment, you want to both push down and pull up on the pedals at the start. Proper core engagement is a must - your legs need a good strong backboard to push against.\n\n\u200b\n\nWe understand that not everyone's trainer has the necessary resistance or the required stability to perform this workout as described. If you can't safely stand up, then you can get much of the same benefit by doing these efforts seated. If your trainer can\u2019t handle the rapid change in speed or does not have high enough resistance at a super low cadence, then you can start the efforts at a higher cadence and treat them as \u201cnormal\u201d all-out sprints.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR < 80%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 4\n\n**Interval **\n\nStanding Start: 20 seconds @ RPE 10 --\n\nStarting from standing (or very very very slow rolling) starts in a 53x14 gear. Really focus on pushing and pulling, try to get on top of the gear as quickly as possible\n\nHold: 1 minute 40 seconds @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP\n\nRecovery: 8 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness. While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are just times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing. Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high, your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week, but only if you do it right! Most people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\"\n\n\u200b\n\nTruth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted. So what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like? For 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70% is ok, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in mid to low Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR, up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can, for most this is 80-90rpm. Also, your RPE should be a 2-4.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right? It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster. You will have to trust us on that one! When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions! Or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 7\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 1\n\n**Interval**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "For help understanding your swim workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/SwimSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\nWorkout Execution:\n\nSwimming from Beach entry- Begin by wading into the water picking the path with least amount of rocks and obstacles that will be safe to perform ins and outs. Begin by running into water and as you progress deeper into the water, be sure you are picking up your legs and raising your knees before duck diving is required. Once the water has reached hip height begin swimming. Once in the water, pick an object and sight every 30 strokes. Complete your effort and on the return, swim back to the beach entry utilize the currents and surge from the waves back in to the beach. Practice Swimming in a straight line and focus on maintaining your technique throughout.\n\n\u200b\n\nLake Shore Entry- Follow the steps above\n\nDock Entry- If safe to do so, check surroundings to be sure they are safe for diving. From a standing start with a slight bend to the knees and your toes gripping the dock, bend forward from the hips keeping your buttocks raised, place one hand on top of the other, then place your head between your arms so that your chin is on your chest. As you push with your legs propel your body forward with your finger tips entering the water first. Once in the water, pick an object and sight every 30 strokes. Practice Swimming in a straight line and focus on maintaining your technique throughout.\n\nPool- Begin by treading water and swim sighting every 30 strokes. Turnaround to be executed without touching the wall. If you have the ability, begin by diving in.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n4 minutes freestyle swim @ RPE 1-2 -- Z1 Pace\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation**\n\n6 minutes- Pick a landmark or object and swim towards it @ RPE 5-6 -- Z3 Pace sighting every 30 strokes.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Set**\n\nPerform 6 Ins and outs. Sight every 30 strokes!!!\n\nSwim @ RPE 7.5-8 -- Z4b Pace for 3 minutes\n\nRecovery: 90 seconds treading water\n\nSwim @ RPE 7.5-8 -- Z4b Pace for 3 minutes\n\nRecovery: 90 seconds\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 1-2 -- Z1 mixing up strokes\n\n\u200b\n\n**Total Distance**\n\n3000m\n",

            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness. While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing. Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high and your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week. Shorter Endurance rides (like this one) can fit in both a hard week of training and a recovery week. That is, only if you do it right! Most people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\"\n\n\u200b\n\nTruth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride, especially one under 90 minutes should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted.\n\nSo what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like? For 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70%, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in low to mid Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can; for most this is 80-90rpm. Also, your RPE should be a 2-4 on a scale of 1-10.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right? It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster, but you will have to trust us on this one! When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions, or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: 4\n\n**Interval**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "(This version of Blender) places a large focus on developing that all-important FTP. The descending time intervals allow for increasing intensity, beginning below threshold and finishing above it, at 105% of your Maximal Aerobic Power (MAP). At the sub-threshold intensities, your body can clear lactate at the same rate or faster than you produce it. As intensity increases however, the clearing rate decreases, resulting in that well-known leg burn. Increasing the intensity in this manner with short recovery periods teaches your body to clear lactate faster so you can ride harder for longer. So get ready to churn through some lactic acid and embrace the burn as the intervals get shorter and harder!\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minute @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 70% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute 30 seconds @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Part 1 **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Part 2 **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n2 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 150% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP-- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Part 3** x8\n\n10 seconds @ RPE 10 -- 200% of FTP -- >105%\n\n1 minute 20 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minute @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "While some of you will know this intensity level as \"Sweet-Spot\", we prefer the name Sub-Threshold, because we want to drive home the fact that you should keep your power below FTP. In the same way that longer Tempo efforts can feel \"easy,\" these shorter Sub-Threshold efforts can also feel \"easy\". After all, if you can hold 100% of FTP for about an hour, then holding less than that for 5-minutes should be a piece of cake right? We know you can go harder for 5-minutes, but that is not what we are asking for.\nThis session is not intended to push you to your limits, nor is it designed to be a massive training load. The real purpose is to essentially keep your fatigue levels right where they are, by giving your body just enough intensity to ensure that you are not \"more recovered\" after today.\nWhile some folks will say that there is no training benefit to such short Sub-Threshold efforts, when viewed in a bigger picture sense (like a 3-week training block) they can be the perfect efforts to ensure you get the most out of a longer training block.\nWe would even ask that you view this session as more of an assessment, rather than strictly a workout. That's because you should be comparing this power output to heart rate response and your own internal RPE. When you have heavy fatigue, your heart rate will struggle to hit its normal peaks. When fresh you would be getting into Z4 heart rate by the end of the last two intervals, and your RPE should never really climb above a 7. When holding onto excess fatigue, your heart rate won't climb above Z3, and your RPE will be above an 8. At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.\nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 3\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 3\n\n**Interval**\n\nSurge: 30 sec @ RPE 8.5 -- 90% of MAP (105-130% of FTP)\n\nSteady: 2 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n8 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "Be very careful when executing this session! Your desire to suffer is strong and the short duration of these intervals will tempt you to push the intensity over your threshold target on this workout. After all, your LT pace is one that you can hold for about an hour, so running at that pace for only 5 minutes is going to feel too easy...and you don't like easy...so make a commitment to stay true to the intensity target that is prescribed.\n\n\u200b\n\nSome reasons for doing short threshold intensity efforts are: to improve recovery time and the ability to repeat the effort after a short rest period, and to do quality work efforts without generating a lot of fatigue that requires significant recovery.\n\n\u200b\n\nFor help understanding your run workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/RunningSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warmup**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2-3 -- 145% of RTP -- HR <70% (Z1-2)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation**\n\n2 x 100m accelerations with 1 minute recovery (jog or walk back to start) in between\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nInterval Duration: 5 minutes\n\nInterval Intensity: 10k pace (RPE 6.5-7 -- 100-110% of RTP -- HR 95-100%) (Z4a)\n\nRecovery duration and intensity: 3 minutes @ RPE 2-4 -- 120-145% of RTP -- HR 70-87% (Z2)\n\nWhen you can no longer keep the pace, the workout is over.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n3-5 minutes @ RPE 2-3 -- 145% of RTP -- HR <70% (Z1-2)\n",

                    "body": "This is a 45 minute run with a 20-minute block at tempo effort. After a proper warmup, you'll start in low zone 3 and decrease the pace (increase the effort) every 5 minutes to finish at the high end of zone 3 or low end of zone 4, just below threshold. The physiological benefits come through increased cardiovascular and muscular endurance and training the body to become more proficient at clearing lactate as it is produced.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis progressive effort will also challenge your mental toughness and ability to continue pushing for more speed as you become increasingly fatigued throughout the session.\n\n\u200b\n\nFor help understanding your run workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/RunningSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2-4 -- 145-120% of RTP -- HR 70-87% (Z1-Z2)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation: Strides**\n\nNumber of Sets: 4\n\nRest Between Sets: 1 min\n\nInterval Distance: 75m build\n\nInterval Effort: Gradually increase from RPE 3-8 (Z2-Z4b)\n\nRecovery: RPE <2 -->145% of RTP -- HR <70% (Z1)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort:**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nNumber of Repeats: NA\n\nRest Between Repeats: NA\n\nInterval Time and Effort:\n\n20 minute continuous build:\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 120% of RTP -- HR 87%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 5.5 -- 115% of RTP -- HR 90%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 110% of RTP -- HR 92%\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 100% of RTP -- HR 95%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5-10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 145% of FTP -- HR <70% (Z1)\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "The short duration, high intensity of these intervals will help develop both your aerobic capacity and VO2 max. You should run these intervals fast, but they're not all out sprints because you only have 30 seconds to recover between each effort. If you start too fast you'll have to slow down on subsequent intervals, and the goal is to run them at the same pace or even get faster toward the end. Aim for mile pace or slightly faster and run on feel as best you can. Your heart rate is not a reliable way to gauge your effort because of the delay in response to intensity change.\n\nThis is a NoVid workout; if you have a treadmill, run along to the workout and enjoy the guided workout as you would a cycling NoVid!\n\n\u200b\n\nFor help understanding your run workout and calculating your pace zones, please see [this article](https://wahoosystm.com/RunningSessionFAQ).\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-up**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2-4 -- 120-145% of RTP -- HR 70-87% (Z2)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Activation 1: Drills of choice: butt kicks, high knees, etc.**\n\nNumber of Sets: 2\n\nRest Between Sets: 30 sec\n\nInterval Distance: 50m\n\nActivation 2: 150-200m Strides\n\nNumber of Sets: 2-3\n\nRest Between Sets: 30-60 seconds\n\nInterval Effort: Build from 120-100% of RTP (Z4a)\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nNumber of Repeats: 8\n\nInterval Duration: 30 seconds\n\nRest Between repeats: 30 seconds\n\nInterval Effort: RPE 8.5 --85% of RTP --HR 100-105% (Z5)\n\nRecovery Effort: RPE 2 -- > 145% of RTP\n\n\\*Heart rate is not a useful metric for recovery effort during this workout because of the very short interval duration. Initially, it may, but by the end of the set, your HR will not decrease very much within the 30 second recovery window.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool-down:**\n\nWalk or jog for 5-10 minutes to cool down (Z1)\n",

                    ],
                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness. While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing. Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high and your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week. Shorter Endurance rides (like this one) can fit in both a hard week of training and a recovery week. That is, only if you do it right! Most people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\"\n\n\u200b\n\nTruth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride, especially one under 90 minutes should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted.\n\nSo what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like? For 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70%, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in low to mid Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can; for most this is 80-90rpm. Also, your RPE should be a 2-4 on a scale of 1-10.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right? It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster, but you will have to trust us on this one! When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions, or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats Per Set: 2\n\n**Interval**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness.  While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are just times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs. \n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing.  Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high, your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week, but only if you do it right!\n\n\u200b\n\nMost people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\" Truth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted. So what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like?\n\nFor 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70% is ok, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in mid to low Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR, up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can, for most this is 80-90rpm and your RPE should be a 2-4 on a scale of 1-10.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right?                     "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness.  While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are just times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs. \n\nThis session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing.  Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high, your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week, but only if you do it right!\n\n\u200b\n\nMost people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\" Truth be told, a proper Zone 2 ride should not leave you fatigued or your legs wasted. So what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like?\n\nFor 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70% is ok, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.) Your heart rate should be sitting in mid to low Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR, up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can, for most this is 80-90rpm and your RPE should be a 2-4 on a scale of 1-10.\n\n\u200b\n\nSounds simple right?  It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster.  You will have to trust us on that one!  When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions!  Or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\nWarm-Up \n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70% \n\n\u200b\n\nMain Effort\n\nNumber of Sets\n\n8.5\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set\n\n1\n\nInterval: 10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\nExtra Volume \n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\nCool Down\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

This gives you the opportunity to practice T2, so make sure to have your running gear set up beforehand. When you finish the first bike session, dismount, transition, and complete the first brick run (details can be found in each of the \u201csplit brick\u201d run workout descriptions ). Upon finishing the run, take a few moments to eat and drink if necessary then hop back on the bike for the second set.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis workout is a great opportunity to practice a negative split pacing technique. Begin the first cycling session at 55% of FTP to get warmed up and gradually increase to 90%. Aim to hold 75-90% of FTP for the last 60-75 minutes.  On the second cycling set, begin at 70% and increase to 90% after 10-15 minutes.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince this is a race pace workout, it is a great time to practice your nutrition strategies prior to race day. Aim to consume 50-75g of carbohydrates per hour. Note that the maximum fuel your body can process in 60 minutes is 90 grams, but only if 60g comes from glucose and 30g from fructose. Unless you know the exact sugar breakdown of your nutrition do not aim for 90g per hour. It is a good idea to weigh yourself before and after this session so you can determine if you are drinking enough. Losing 1-2 pounds of water weight during this session is okay, any more than that and you need to reassess your hydration plan.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **(Only prior to first cycling session)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 2\n\nRest Between Sets: Running sessions\n\n**Intervals**\n\nSet 1: 75 minutes @ RPE 5-6 -- 75-91% of FTP -- HR <90% (Z3)\n\nSet 2: 45 minutes @ RPE 5-6 -- 75-91% of FTP -- HR <90% (Z3)\n\nRecovery: NA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\nNA - Straight into Run!\n",

Losing 1-2 pounds of water weight during this session is okay, any more than that and you need to reassess your hydration plan.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **(Only prior to first cycling session)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 2\n\nRest Between Sets: Your first Run session\n\n**Interval**\n\nSet 1: 90 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 70-75% of FTP -- HR <90% (Z3)\n\nSet 2: 60 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 70-75% of FTP -- HR <90% (Z3)\n\nRecovery: NA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\nNA - Straight into Run 2!\n",

This gives you the opportunity to practice T2, so make sure to have your running gear set up beforehand. When you finish the first bike session, dismount, transition, and complete the first brick run (details can be found in each of the \u201csplit brick\u201d run workout descriptions ). Upon finishing the run, take a few moments to eat and drink if necessary then hop back on the bike for the second set.\n\nThis workout is a great opportunity to practice a negative split pacing technique. Begin the first cycling session at 55% of FTP to get warmed up and gradually increase to 75%. Aim to hold 75% of FTP for at least the last 90 minutes. On the second cycling set, begin at 70% and increase to 75% after 10-15 minutes.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince this is a race pace workout, it is a great time to practice your nutrition strategies prior to race day. Aim to consume 50-75g of carbohydrates per hour. Note that the maximum fuel your body can process in 60 minutes is 90 grams, but only if 60g comes from glucose and 30g from fructose. Unless you know the exact sugar breakdown of your nutrition do not aim for 90g per hour.\n\nIt is a good idea to weigh yourself before and after this session so you can determine if you are drinking enough. Losing 1-2 pounds of water weight during this session is okay, any more than that and you need to reassess your hydration plan.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **(Only prior to first cycling session)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 2\n\nRest Between Sets: Your first Run session\n\nSet 1: 2 hours @ RPE 5 -- 70-75% of FTP -- HR <90% (Z3)\n\nSet 2: 90 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 70-75% of FTP -- HR <90% (Z3)\n\n\u200b\n\nRecovery:** **\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\nNA - Straight into Run 2!\n",

            "__typename": "Content",
            "bannerImage": null,
            "category": "Mixed",
            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/b9606296-cab6-4c2c-81b2-340f9e967e6c-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "While some of you will know this intensity level as \"Sweet-Spot\", we prefer the name Sub-Threshold, because we want to drive home the fact that you should keep your power below FTP. In the same way that longer Tempo efforts can feel \"easy,\" these shorter Sub-Threshold efforts can also feel \"easy\". After all, if you can hold 100% of FTP for about an hour, then holding less than that for 5-minutes should be a piece of cake right? We know you can go harder for 5-minutes, but that is not what we are asking for.\n\n\u200b\n\nThis session is not intended to push you to your limits, nor is it designed to be a massive training load. The real purpose is to essentially keep your fatigue levels right where they are, by giving your body just enough intensity to ensure that you are not \"more recovered\" after today.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhile some folks will say that there is no training benefit to such short Sub-Threshold efforts, when viewed in a bigger picture sense (like a 3-week training block) they can be the perfect efforts to ensure you get the most out of a longer training block.\n\n\u200b\n\nWe would even ask that you view this session as more of an assessment, rather than strictly a workout. That's because you should be comparing this power output to heart rate response and your own internal RPE. When you have heavy fatigue, your heart rate will struggle to hit its normal peaks. When fresh you would be getting into Z4 heart rate by the end of the last two intervals, and your RPE should never really climb above a 7. When holding onto excess fatigue, your heart rate won't climb above Z3, and your RPE will be above an 8. At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.\n\n\u200b\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70% \n\n1 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75% \n\n1 minute @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80% \n\n1 minute @ RPE 5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85% \n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90% \n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <95% \n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP) \n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 4 \n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75% \n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 4 \n\n**Interval** \n\nSurge: 30 sec @ RPE 8.5 -- 90% of MAP (105-130% of FTP) \n\nSteady: 1 minutes 30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n13 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }
