                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "While some of you will know this intensity level as \"Sweet-Spot\", we prefer the name Sub-Threshold, because we want to drive home the fact that you should keep your power below FTP. In the same way that longer Tempo efforts can feel \"easy,\" these shorter Sub-Threshold efforts can also feel \"easy\". After all, if you can hold 100% of FTP for about an hour, then holding less than that for 5-minutes should be a piece of cake right? We know you can go harder for 5-minutes, but that is not what we are asking for.\n\n\nThis session is not intended to push you to your limits, nor is it designed to be a massive training load. The real purpose is to essentially keep your fatigue levels right where they are, by giving your body just enough intensity to ensure that you are not \"more recovered\" after today.\n\n\nWhile some folks will say that there is no training benefit to such short Sub-Threshold efforts, when viewed in a bigger picture sense (like a 3-week training block) they can be the perfect efforts to ensure you get the most out of a longer training block.\n\n\nWe would even ask that you view this session as more of an assessment, rather than strictly a workout. That's because you should be comparing this power output to heart rate response and your own internal RPE. When you have heavy fatigue, your heart rate will struggle to hit its normal peaks. When fresh you would be getting into Z4 heart rate by the end of the last two intervals, and your RPE should never really climb above a 7. When holding onto excess fatigue, your heart rate won't climb above Z3, and your RPE will be above an 8. At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.\n\n\nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 110% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 3\n\n**Interval **\n\nEffort: 25 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 87% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\nRecovery: 15 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n25 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

            "defaultImage": "https://systm-test-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/content/74020b17-9a41-472d-b1af-8af526b49d50-cycling_NoVid_library.png",
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "The idea behind this session can be seen in Who Dares, Fight Club, and Standing Starts into sustained efforts. Your bodies ability to clear out metabolites and process oxygen is nearly identical between 90% of FTP and 100% of FTP, the difference is that at 100% of FTP your body is producing those metabolites at the same rate it is clearing them. At 90% of FTP your body can clear things at the same rate, but your body isn't producing them at the same rate.\n\nLong Sub-Threshold efforts represent an effort that your body can just about handle (assuming you are properly fueled and not completely exhausted), clearing things out faster than they can accumulate. To really stress that clearance rate each of these Sub-Threshold efforts start with a 20-second effort well above FTP. By the time you settle into the Sub-Threshold effort, your body will be flooded with those metabolites that cause your legs and lungs to burn. However, since you are below FTP (clearing things out faster than you are producing them), the concentration of those metabolites will slowly drop over the course of the whole effort. Not only does this train your body to clear things faster, but it will also mentally prepare for the discomfort associated with efforts above FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nFor this session, we are asking you to dance on that razor's edge of your FTP, ideally the side that allows you to complete the session. If your legs or lungs aren't feeling great, you are better off dropping the steady effort by 5% and keeping the starting effort at 100%. Another component of this is settling into a good rhythm of breathing and pedaling. Everyone has a preferred cadence, and this is an instance where your preferred cadence supersedes the cadence targets onscreen. We want you dancing right on that edge of your comfort, and you can get much closer to that edge riding your preferred cadence.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: 3\n\nRest between sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 seconds @ RPE 9.5 -- 180% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n55 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

At the same time, if you have gained a significant amount of fitness, your Heart Rate will stay in Z3, and your RPE won't climb above 6. The secondary tell between improved fitness and fatigue is how quickly your heart rate drops after each effort. When fatigued, your heart rate won't drop below Z2 during the recovery.\n\nWhile it is easy to rely solely on Power, you should always refer back to RPE and Heart Rate, and today is the perfect session to practice comparing the 3.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 8\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort: 4 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\nRecovery: 5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n3 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- <45% of FTP -- HR < 60%\n",

                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "The idea behind this session can be seen in Who Dares, Fight Club, and Standing Starts into sustained efforts. Your bodies ability to clear out metabolites and process oxygen is nearly identical between 90% of FTP and 100% of FTP, the difference is that at 100% of FTP your body is producing those metabolites at the same rate it is clearing them.  At 90% of FTP your body can clear things at the same rate, but your body isn't producing them at the same rate.  \n\nLong Sub-Threshold efforts represent an effort that your body can just about handle (assuming you are properly fueled and not completely exhausted), clearing things out faster than they can accumulate.  To really stress that clearance rate each of these Sub-Threshold efforts start with a 20-second effort well above FTP.  By the time you settle into the Sub-Threshold effort, your body will be flooded with those metabolites that cause your legs and lungs to burn.  However, since you are below FTP (clearing things out faster than you are producing them), the concentration of those metabolites will slowly drop over the course of the whole effort.  Not only does this train your body to clear things faster, but it will also mentally prepare for the discomfort associated with efforts above FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nFor this session, we are asking you to dance on that razor's edge of your FTP, ideally the side that allows you to complete the session.  If your legs or lungs aren't feeling great, you are better off dropping the steady effort by 5% and keeping the starting effort at 100%.\n\nAnother component of this is settling into a good rhythm of breathing and pedaling.  Everyone has a preferred cadence, and this is an instance where your preferred cadence supersedes the cadence targets onscreen.  We want you dancing right on that edge of your comfort, and you can get much closer to that edge riding your preferred cadence.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 5.5 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of sets: 2\n\nRest between sets: \n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval repeats per set: NA \n\n**Interval**\n\n20 seconds @ RPE 9.5 -- 180% of FTP -- HR >105%\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 6.5 -- 90% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n25 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down **\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 50% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Tempo efforts are not maximal, and often feel too \"easy\", leading many people to turn a tempo effort into a Sub-Threshold or even Supra-Threshold effort. That is not the point! If we wanted you to go harder, you would see a different workout in your Training Plan. We know you can go harder for 25-minutes, but that is not the point of a Tempo Session.\n\n\u200b\n\nWhat many people don't realize is that your body's ability to process oxygen and metabolites is nearly identical from 80%-100% of FTP. The main change across that intensity range is the rate at which those metabolites are being generated. While you would get a slightly greater training load from doing this session at higher power, you would be adding more fatigue to your system than we want. That extra fatigue means you either need to ease off your workouts in the days leading up or ease off your workouts on the days after. From a big picture point of view that's no good! This session gives a great steady-state aerobic training load while leaving you fresh enough that you can hit training hard the days before and after. That means your training load over the entire week is often higher when you maintain restraint and stick to those Tempo Targets.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 6 -- 85% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n6 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 4\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort: 8 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\nRecovery: 12 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume **\n\n45 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"

            "__typename": "Content",

            "category": "Endurance",
            "channel": "Wmrk3N9mqG",
            "defaultImage": null,
            "descriptions": [
                {
                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [
                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "Tempo sessions are always a great time to work on pace control, especially Tempo efforts longer than 30 minutes. We are taking that pacing demand a bit further in this session by forcing you to slightly increase your effort as time goes on. This is referred to as a \"Negative-Split\", meaning the second half is faster (or you hold a higher power) than the first half.\n\nWhile you might question the benefit of doing \"easier\" tempo efforts, the truth is when riding between 80% and 100% of FTP your body processes oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate. Holding a higher power will give you a higher single day training stimulus, but looking at the big picture that can have its drawbacks. Mainly the fatigue those harder sessions cause, which requires easier workouts the days before and after. Sticking to the Tempo targets gets you nearly the same training stimulus while allowing you to hit harder sessions the rest of the week.\n\nThis session contains a single 60-minute tempo effort, broken into three 20-minute segments. You will spend the first 20-minutes at 80% of FTP, the next 20 at 84%, and the final 20 at 87%. By the time you hit the last 10-minutes of this effort, that 87% will feel much harder than it should. Another way of thinking about this one, if you were to reverse the order, and start at 87%, what you would likely find is that your RPE stays fairly consistent for the entire effort, even though the power targets are dropping.\n\nOverheating, not drinking enough, being under-fueled, mental fatigue, all of these will play a factor in how you feel in that final block. They will also impact your heart rate. While these power targets are usually associated with Zone 3 heart rate, many people will see their heart rate climb into low Z4 if they are not hydrating properly, or have inadequate cooling.\nThis can be a great session to act as a \"wake up call\" on any poor training habits you might have, so take note of them and aim to address those issues during your next workout.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: NA\nRest between sets: NA\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n20 minutes@ RPE 6.5 -- 84% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 87% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
                }

                        {
                            "__typename": "Alert",
                            "icon": null,
                            "message": "This session can be completed outside by writing down the interval breakdown in the description. (We are working on the ability to push the workout directly to your Wahoo ELEMNT.)",
                            "severity": "Warning"
                        }
                    ],
                    "body": "With repeated 2-minute long MAP intervals, this session can be viewed as a middle ground between Revolver with its 1 minute MAP efforts and Nine Hammers with its 3-4-minute MAP/FTP efforts. The goal of this session is to accumulate a significant amount of time near your VO2max, or the point at which your body is consuming as much oxygen as it possibly can. That means your heart rate and breathing rate will both be near their max by the end of each interval, especially in the final few intervals.\n\n\u200b\n\nSince it takes time for your heart rate and breathing rate to match your effort, for the first part of each interval, you will be tapping into your Anaerobic Capacity to produce the required power. To account for this, we have limited the recovery duration to be equal to the interval duration. Limited recovery ensures that you will drain your Anaerobic Capacity before the end of the intervals, meaning your body will be forced to produce as much power as possible using oxygen.\n\nPushing your aerobic system to its max like this is not just great for improving MAP, but also your FTP. Since MAP limits your FTP, improving your MAP is vital to the continued growth of your FTP. By the end of this session, you will have accumulated 20-minutes near your Maximal Aerobic Power, which will leave your legs aching and your lungs burning.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up **\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <65%\n\n4 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n2 minute @ RPE 3.5 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <80%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 4.5 -- 75% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n30 seconds @ RPE 9 -- 90-95% of AC (130-180% of FTP)\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: N/A\n\nInterval Repeats Per set: 8\n\n**Interval**\n\nEffort: 2 minutes @ RPE 9 -- 100% of MAP (115-135% of FTP)\n\nRecovery: 2 minutes @ RPE 2 -- <45% of FTP\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n1 hour @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "__typename": "Description",
                    "alerts": [],
                    "body": "The goal of this workout is to help develop your baseline aerobic fitness. While we are all about the High-Intensity Interval Training that most of our videos dish out, there are just times in a well-structured training plan that a proper Endurance/Base ride is just what your body needs. This session will add minimal fatigue to your system, while still giving your aerobic engine the workload it needs to continue progressing. Steady Long Endurance rides are one of the best ways to cap off a long 2 or 3-week training block when your fatigue is high, your legs are tired, but you have just a bit more to squeeze out of yourself before you take your rest week. Shorter Endurance rides (like this one) can fit in both a hard week of training and a recovery week. That is, only if you do it right!\n\nMost people ride too hard when they head out for their \"base miles.\"\n\nSo what does a \"proper\" Zone 2 ride look like?\n\nFor 90% of the ride, you should stay between 55% and 65% of your FTP, at times going up to 70%, but not over. (To spice things up, we have broken this session into 10-minute segments alternating from 60 to 65% of FTP.)\n\nYour heart rate should be sitting in mid to low Zone 2 heart rate, which is 70-80% of LTHR, up to 85% of LTHR, but not for long. It would be best if you held the highest comfortable cadence you can, for most this is 80-90rpm\n\nAlso, your RPE should be a 2-3\n\nSounds simple right? It's actually one of the harder sessions to get right because you spend most of the time questioning why you are riding so easy, and if this is really going to make you fitter and faster. You will have to trust us on that one! When you see this session in your Training Plan, follow these instructions! Or you might just pay for it when your next hard session comes around.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm-Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of Sets: 1\n\nRest Between Sets: 10 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\nInterval Repeats per Set: 13\n\n**Interval**\n\n10 minutes @ RPE 4 -- 65% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nN/A\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

                    "body": "**What? **\n\nA trail ride at a cruisy pace.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Why? **\n\nVariety is the spice of life and it\u2019s also the best way to accomplish a few goals simultaneously. Focus on targeting your weaknesses during this trail session in order to improve them come race day.\n\n\u200b\n\n**How? **\n\nThis is an unstructured ride - let the trail do the thinking today. If you find a section that you struggle to hit cleanly, repeat that section a few times until you feel comfortable with it. Don\u2019t feel the need to practice every section you struggle with on a single ride, you can always come back another day! Keep the effort below 85% of FTP at all times and spend the bulk of the ride at 55% of FTP.\n\n\u200b\n\nMake sure to warm up before and cool down afterwards.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <65%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort **\n\nNumber of Sets 1 \n\nRest Between Sets N/A \n\nInterval Repeats Per Set 1 \n\nInterval Steady: 45 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75% \n\nEffort: 20 minutes @ RPE 5 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <90% \n\nSteady: 45 minutes @ RPE 3 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <75%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\nNA\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 2 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",

Aim to consume 50-75g of carbohydrates per hour. _Note that the maximum fuel your body can process in 60 minutes is 90 grams, but only if 60g comes from glucose and 30g from fructose. Unless you know the exact sugar break down of your nutrition do not aim for 90g per hour_\n\n\u200b\n\nIt is also a good idea to weigh yourself before and after this session so you can determine if you are drinking enough. Unless you know the exact sugar break down of your nutrition do not aim for 90g per hour_\n\nIt is also a good idea to weigh yourself before and after this session so you can determine if you are drinking enough.                             "__typename": "Alert",

                    "body": "Tempo sessions are always a great time to work on pace control, especially Tempo efforts longer than 30 minutes. We are taking that pacing demand a bit further in this session by forcing you to slightly increase your effort as time goes on. This is referred to as a \"Negative-Split\", meaning the second half is faster (or you hold a higher power) than the first half.\n\nWhile you might question the benefit of doing \"easier\" tempo efforts, the truth is when riding between 80% and 100% of FTP your body processes oxygen and metabolites at nearly the same rate. Holding a higher power will give you a higher single day training stimulus, but looking at the big picture that can have its drawbacks. Mainly the fatigue those harder sessions cause, which requires easier workouts the days before and after. Sticking to the Tempo targets gets you nearly the same training stimulus while allowing you to hit harder sessions the rest of the week.\n\nThis session contains a single 60-minute tempo effort, broken into three 20-minute segments. You will spend the first 20-minutes at 80% of FTP, the next 20 at 84%, and the final 20 at 87%. By the time you hit the last 10-minutes of this effort, that 87% will feel much harder than it should. Another way of thinking about this one, if you were to reverse the order, and start at 87%, what you would likely find is that your RPE stays fairly consistent for the entire effort, even though the power targets are dropping.\n\nOverheating, not drinking enough, being under-fueled, mental fatigue, all of these will play a factor in how you feel in that final block. They will also impact your heart rate. While these power targets are usually associated with Zone 3 heart rate, many people will see their heart rate climb into low Z4 if they are not hydrating properly, or have inadequate cooling.\nThis can be a great session to act as a \"wake up call\" on any poor training habits you might have, so take note of them and aim to address those issues during your next workout.\n\n\u200b\n\n**Warm Up**\n\n30 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7 -- 95% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 7.5 -- 100% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n1 minute @ RPE 8 -- 105% of FTP -- HR <100%\n\n7 minutes @ RPE 2.5 -- 55% of FTP -- HR <70%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Main Effort**\n\nNumber of sets: NA\n\nRest between sets: NA\n\nInterval repeats per: NA\n\n\n**Interval**\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 6 -- 80% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n20 minutes@ RPE 6.5 -- 84% of FTP -- HR <90%\n\n20 minutes @ RPE 7 -- 87% of FTP -- HR <95%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Extra Volume**\n\n15 minutes @ RPE 3.5 -- 60% of FTP -- HR <85%\n\n\u200b\n\n**Cool Down**\n\n5 minutes @ RPE 1.5 -- 45% of FTP -- HR <70%\n",
                    "title": "Description"
